[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] The Micronaut Framework is a modern, JVM-based, full stack Java framework designed for building modular, easily testable JVM applications with support for Java, Kotlin, and Groovy.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] The Micronaut framework was originally created by a team who had also worked on the Grails framework.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] The Micronaut framework takes inspiration from lessons learned over the years building real-world applications from monoliths to microservices using Spring, Spring Boot and the Grails framework.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] The core team continues to develop and maintain the Micronaut project through the support of the Micronaut Foundation.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] Historically, frameworks such as Spring and Grails were not designed to run in scenarios such as serverless functions, Android apps, or low memory footprint microservices.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] In contrast, the Micronaut framework is designed to be suitable for all of these scenarios.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] This goal is achieved through the use of Java’s annotation processors, which are usable on any JVM language that supports them, as well as an HTTP Server (with several runtimes Netty, Jetty, Tomcat, Undertow…) and an HTTP Client (with several runtimes Netty, Java HTTP Client, …).
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] To provide a similar programming model to Spring and Grails, these annotation processors precompile the necessary metadata to perform DI, define AOP proxies and configure your application to run in a low-memory environment.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] Many APIs in the Micronaut framework are heavily inspired by Spring and Grails.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] This is by design, and helps bring developers up to speed quickly.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] Micronaut Framework 5.0.x continues the work started in the first 5.0 milestones and adds a number of improvements across the core container, HTTP stack, configuration system, and developer-facing APIs.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] This page is a curated overview of the most important additions on the `5.0.x` line.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] For upgrade guidance, see Upgrading your Micronaut Application, and for incompatible changes, review Breaking Changes.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] Micronaut Framework 5 modernizes the core platform with newer JVM and language support, including a new JDK 25 baseline, an Apache Groovy 5 baseline, a Kotlin 2.3 baseline, broader support for current JDK capabilities, and deeper investment in compile-time metadata.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] See also Breaking Changes for version-specific migration notes.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] The framework APIs now embrace nullability annotations and specifically JSpecify nullability annotations, with `@NullMarked` adoption across the codebase and stronger static analysis integration.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] The result is clearer API contracts, improved Kotlin interoperability, and better IDE feedback.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] The IoC container and compile-time infrastructure also received substantial work in the 5.0 branch.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] Bean resolution, qualifier handling, replacement metadata, eager initialization, and runtime annotation processing were refined to reduce runtime work and improve predictability.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] The bean context was reworked in several areas during the 5.0 development cycle, including precomputed bean indexes, compile-time `@Replaces` handling, and broader bean context optimizations.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] Together, these changes continue Micronaut’s focus on startup performance and low runtime overhead.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] Micronaut 5 also added support for creating AOP proxies at runtime when build-time proxy generation is not the right fit.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] This enables integrations such as Byte Buddy-based proxies, JDK dynamic proxies for interfaces, and test-oriented proxy scenarios such as mocks and spies.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] For background on Micronaut’s AOP model, see Aspect Oriented Programming.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] Recent 5.0.x work also improved interoperability with Jakarta APIs by adding support for `jakarta.annotation.Priority`, mapping it to Micronaut ordering semantics for beans and HTTP filters.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] Related ordering documentation can be found in Injectable Container Types and Filter Order.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] On the HTTP side, HTTP/3 support on the Netty stack was promoted to stable.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] See HTTP/3 Support and HTTP/3 in Clients.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] The 5.0 line also includes a multipart/form handling refactor that introduces a lower-level, more server-independent form API and improves resource management in higher-level binders.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] See Forms, Detailed Form API, and File Uploads.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] Configuration support expanded significantly in 5.0.x.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] Micronaut now supports config imports and a `PropertySourceImporter` SPI, enabling configuration loading from sources such as files, classpath locations, environment variables, config trees, and custom importer implementations.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] See Importing Additional Configuration, Implementing a Custom PropertySourceImporter, and Externalized Configuration with PropertySources.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] Configuration metadata also became more useful for tooling.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] Micronaut 5 can generate JSON Schema documents from `@ConfigurationProperties`, making it easier to drive IDE completion, validation, and external tooling from the same configuration model used by the framework.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] For the underlying configuration model, see Configuration Properties.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] The JSON and serialization stack was updated as well, with work across `JsonMapper`, the update to Jackson 3, and additional configuration coverage so applications can adopt the newer JSON infrastructure more smoothly.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] Micronaut Retry gained programmatic retry and circuit breaker APIs in addition to the existing annotation-driven model documented in Retry Advice.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] This makes it possible to define typed retry and circuit breaker policies in code and reuse them for synchronous, reactive, and asynchronous flows.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] The 5.0.x line also expanded context propagation capabilities, including support for scoped values and continued alignment with modern JDK context propagation patterns.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] For teams adopting Micronaut Framework 5.0.x, the biggest benefits are stronger null-safety, more flexible AOP and retry models, better HTTP and multipart capabilities, richer configuration tooling, and continued improvements to the container’s compile-time-first runtime model.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] Check Micronaut Upgrade documentation to help you upgrade your Micronaut applications.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] To learn what’s new, check the GitHub Release notes for each module you’re interested in.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] They contain a summary of all changes broken down by type.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] Review the section on Breaking Changes and update your affected application code.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] The following sections walk you through a Quick Start on how to use the Micronaut framework to set up a basic "Hello World" application.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] Before getting started ensure you have a Java 8 or higher JDK installed, and it is recommended that you use a suitable IDE such as IntelliJ IDEA.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] The Micronaut CLI is an optional but convenient way to create Micronaut applications.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] The best way to install Micronaut CLI on Unix systems is with SDKMAN which greatly simplifies installing and managing multiple Micronaut versions.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] To see all available installation methods, check the Micronaut Starter documentation.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] Using the Micronaut CLI you can create a new Micronaut application in either Groovy, Java, or Kotlin (the default is Java).
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] The previous steps created a new Java application in a directory called `hello-world` featuring a Gradle build.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] If you have created a Maven-based project, use `./mvnw mn:run` instead.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] By default, the Micronaut HTTP server is configured to run on port 8080.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] See the section Running Server on a Specific Port for more options.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] To create a service that responds to "Hello World" you first need a controller.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] If you use Java, place the previous file in `src/main/java/hello/world`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] If you use Groovy, place the previous file in `src/main/groovy/hello/world`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] If you use Kotlin, place the previous file in `src/main/kotlin/hello/world`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] This is the class that is run when starting the application via Gradle/Maven or via deployment.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] You can also run the main class directly within your IDE.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] To import a Micronaut project into IntelliJ IDEA, open the `build.gradle` or `pom.xml` file and follow the instructions to import the project.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] Once you have enabled annotation processing in IntelliJ you can run the application and tests directly within the IDE without the need of an external build tool such as Gradle or Maven.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] These extensions can be installed by clicking on the **Install** button in the banner of the pages linked above, or, by searching for the extensions within VS Code.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] Once the extensions are installed just type `code .` in any Micronaut project directory and the project will be opened within VS Code.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] To use Eclipse IDE, it is recommended you import your Micronaut project into Eclipse using either Gradle BuildShip for Gradle or M2Eclipse for Maven.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] Once these are installed, import the project by selecting `File → Import` and choosing `Maven → Existing Maven Project` and navigating to the root directory of your project (where the `pom.xml` file is located).
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] Then enable annotation processing by opening `Eclipse → Preferences` and navigating to `Maven → Annotation Processing` and selecting the option `Automatically configure JDT APT`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] Apache NetBeans can open Maven and Gradle projects out of the box.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] Make sure that the **Java Web and EE** feature is enabled at `Tools → Plugins → Installed`, in order to have additional support for Micronaut, like code completion for configuration and data elements.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] As mentioned previously, the Micronaut framework includes both an HTTP server and an HTTP client.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] A low-level HTTP client is provided which you can use to test the `HelloController` created in the previous section.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] In addition to a low-level client, the Micronaut framework features a declarative, compile-time HTTP client, powered by the Client annotation.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] The Client annotation produces an implementation automatically for you at compile time without the using proxies or runtime reflection.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] See the section on the Micronaut HTTP Client for more information.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] To deploy a Micronaut application you create an executable JAR file by running `./gradlew assemble` or `./mvnw package`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] The constructed JAR file can then be executed with `java -jar`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] The executable JAR can be run locally, or deployed to a virtual machine or managed Cloud service that supports executable JARs.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] Dependency Injection (often referred to as Inversion of Control) is a pattern that allows your code to remain independent of configuration and allows the definition of loosely coupled applications.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] Reducing coupling increases the ability to test your application by ensuring code is not tied directly to an external systems (like a database).
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] Unlike other frameworks which rely on runtime reflection and proxies, the Micronaut framework uses compile time data to implement dependency injection.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] This is a similar approach taken by tools such as Google Dagger, which is designed primarily with Android in mind.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] Micronaut, on the other hand, is designed for building server-side microservices and provides many of the same tools and utilities as other frameworks but without using reflection or caching excessive amounts of reflection metadata.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] Note that the IoC part of the Micronaut framework can be used completely independently of Micronaut for whatever application type you wish to build.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] To do so, configure your build to include the `micronaut-inject-java` dependency as an annotation processor.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] If you are creating custom compile-time annotations or annotation mappers, see Annotation Metadata for additional requirements around `AnnotationMapper`, `NamedAnnotationMapper`, and `TypedAnnotationMapper`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] The easiest way to do this is with Micronaut’s Gradle or Maven plugins.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] The entry point for IoC is then the ApplicationContext interface, which includes a `run` method.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] A bean is an object whose lifecycle is managed by the Micronaut IoC container.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] That lifecycle may include creation, execution, and destruction.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] Micronaut implements the JSR-330 (jakarta.inject) - Dependency Injection for Java specification, hence to use Micronaut you simply use the annotations provided by jakarta.inject.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] The Micronaut framework automatically discovers dependency injection metadata on the classpath and wires the beans together according to injection points you define.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] At this point, you may be wondering how Micronaut framework performs the above dependency injection without requiring reflection.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] The key is a set of AST transformations (for Groovy) and annotation processors (for Java) that generate classes that implement the BeanDefinition interface.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] Micronaut framework uses the ASM bytecode library to generate classes, and because Micronaut knows ahead of time the injection points, there is no need to scan all methods, fields, constructors, etc. at runtime like other frameworks such as Spring do.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] Also, since reflection is not used when constructing the bean, the JVM can inline and optimize the code far better, resulting in better runtime performance and reduced memory consumption.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] This is particularly important for non-singleton scopes where application performance depends on bean creation performance.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] In addition, with Micronaut framework your application startup time and memory consumption are not affected by the size of your codebase in the same way as with a framework that uses reflection.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] Reflection-based IoC frameworks load and cache reflection data for every single field, method, and constructor in your code.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] Thus, as your code grows in size so do your memory requirements, whilst with Micronaut this is not the case.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] To help you easily understand what Micronaut is doing at startup and when a particular bean is created Micronaut includes a dependency injection tracing feature which can be activated in a number of different ways including via the ApplicationContextBuilder API.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] The simplest way to activate injection trace mode is using an environment variable.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] The BeanContext is a container object for all your bean definitions (it also implements BeanDefinitionRegistry).
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] It is also the point of initialization for Micronaut.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] Generally speaking however, you don’t interact directly with the `BeanContext` API and can simply use `jakarta.inject` annotations and the annotations in the io.micronaut.context.annotation package for your dependency injection needs.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] Constructor injection is when dependencies are injected into the constructor for a type.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] The example in the next section uses constructor injection.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] In the above example retrieving the `Vehicle` type from the BeanContext will result in calling the `Vehicle(Engine engine)` constructor which will in turn resolve the `Engine` using the `getDefault()` method since it is annotated with `@Creator`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] If there are multiple possible candidates for a particular constructor argument a qualifier can be specified (such as `jakarta.inject.Named`) to disambiguate the injection.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] If it is not possible to disambiguate then the result will be a NonUniqueBeanException.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] See the Qualifiers section for more information.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] Trying to inject a field that is declared `final` will result in a compilation error.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] Field injection should be seen as inferior to constructor injection as explained in the previous sections since it can result in the code being less-structured, harder to read and harder to test.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] You can inject methods by annotating the method with `jakarta.inject.Inject`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] For each argument of the method Micronaut will attempt to resolve the method argument as a bean.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] If any of the methods are not resolvable a NoSuchBeanException will be thrown.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] Method injection can be useful if you need post construction initializers, however in general should be avoided in favour of constructor injection where possible.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] Occasionally it is desirable for injection to be optional (ie. not fail with a NoSuchBeanException if there is no candidate bean available).
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] For example if you are trying to build an extensible system where a default implementation is provided by the type but consumers of your API can provide a bean that, if available, will be injected.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] When injecting a collection of beans, they are not ordered by default.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] Implement the Ordered interface to inject an ordered collection.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] If the requested bean type does not implement Ordered, Micronaut framework searches for the @Order annotation on beans.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] The @Order annotation is especially useful for ordering beans created by factories where the bean type is a class in a third-party library.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] In this example, both `LowRateLimit` and `HighRateLimit` implement the `RateLimit` interface.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] When a collection of `RateLimit` beans are requested from the context, they are returned in ascending order based on the value in the annotation.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] Micronaut maps jakarta.annotation.Priority to @Order at build time, so @Priority values are treated the same as @Order and follow the same ascending numeric precedence (lower numbers mean higher precedence).
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] When injecting a single instance of a bean the @Order annotation can also be used to define which bean has the highest precedence and hence should be injected.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] Micronaut also maps jakarta.annotation.Priority to @Order at build time, so the same mapped @Priority numeric semantics determine which bean has the highest precedence for single-bean injection.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] If you have multiple possible implementations for a given interface to inject, you need to use a qualifier.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p01] Once again Micronaut framework leverages JSR-330 and the Qualifier and Named annotations to support this use case.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p02] To qualify by name, use the Named annotation.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p02] You can also declare @Named at the class level of a bean to explicitly define the name of the bean.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p02] In addition to being able to qualify by name, you can build your own qualifiers using the Qualifier annotation.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p02] The above annotation is itself annotated with the `@Qualifier` annotation to designate it as a qualifier.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p02] You can then use the annotation at any injection point in your code.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p02] Since Micronaut framework 3.0, annotation qualifiers can also use annotation members to resolve the correct bean to inject.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p02] You can then use the `@Cylinders` qualifier on any injection point to select the correct bean to inject.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p02] Since Micronaut framework 3.0, it is possible to select which bean to inject based on the generic type arguments of the class or interface.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p02] The `CylinderProvider` interface provides the number of cylinders.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p02] You can define implementations of the `Engine` interface with different generic type arguments.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p02] The above defines a `V6` class that implements the `CylinderProvider` interface.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p02] The above defines a `V8` class that implements the `CylinderProvider` interface.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p02] In the above example the `V8Engine` bean is injected.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p02] Primary is a qualifier that indicates that a bean is the primary bean to be selected in the case of multiple interface implementations.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p02] The `Green` bean class implements `ColorPicker` and is annotated with `@Primary`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p02] The `Blue` bean class also implements `ColorPicker` and hence you have two possible candidates when injecting the `ColorPicker` interface.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p02] Since `Green` is the primary, it will always be favoured.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p02] If multiple possible candidates are present and no `@Primary` is defined a NonUniqueBeanException is thrown.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p02] In addition to `@Primary`, there is also a Secondary annotation which causes the opposite effect and allows de-prioritizing a bean.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p02] The @Any qualifier is typically used in conjunction with the BeanProvider interface to allow more dynamic use cases.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p02] If there are multiple beans you can also adapt the behaviour.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p02] By default, when you annotate a bean with a scope such as `@Singleton` the bean class and all interfaces it implements and super classes it extends from become injectable via `@Inject`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p02] In the above case other classes in your application can choose to either inject the interface `Engine` or the concrete implementation `V8Engine`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p02] If this is undesirable you can use the `typed` member of the @Bean annotation to limit the exposed types.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p02] Micronaut framework features an extensible bean scoping mechanism based on JSR-330.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p02] Additional scopes can be added by defining a `@Singleton` bean that implements the CustomScope interface.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p02] Note that when starting an ApplicationContext, by default `@Singleton`-scoped beans are created lazily and on-demand.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p02] This is by design to optimize startup time.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p02] If this presents a problem for your use case you have the option of using the @Context annotation which binds the lifecycle of your object to the lifecycle of the ApplicationContext.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p02] In other words when the ApplicationContext is started your bean will be created.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p02] Alternatively, annotate any `@Singleton`-scoped bean with @Parallel which allows parallel initialization of your bean without impacting overall startup time.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p02] Eager initialization of `@Singleton` beans maybe desirable in certain scenarios, such as on AWS Lambda where more CPU resources are assigned to Lambda construction than execution.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p02] When you use Micronaut framework in environments such as Serverless Functions, you will not have an Application class, and instead you extend a Micronaut-provided class.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p02] @ConfigurationReader beans such as @EachProperty or @ConfigurationProperties are singleton beans.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p02] The following example illustrates `@Refreshable` scope behavior.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p02] If you invoke `latestForecast()` twice, you will see identical responses such as `"Scattered Clouds 01/Feb/18 10:29.199"`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p02] When the `/refresh` endpoint is invoked or a RefreshEvent is published, the instance is invalidated and a new instance is created the next time the object is requested.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p02] Scopes can be defined on meta annotations that you can then apply to your classes.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p02] In the example above the `@Singleton` annotation is applied to the `@Driver` annotation which results in every class that is annotated with `@Driver` being regarded as singleton.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p02] Note that in this case it is not possible to alter the scope when the annotation is applied.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p02] In many cases, you may want to make available as a bean a class that is not part of your codebase such as those provided by third-party libraries.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p02] In this case, you cannot annotate the compiled class.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p02] A factory is a class annotated with the Factory annotation that provides one or more methods annotated with a bean scope annotation.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p02] Which annotation you use depends on what scope you want the bean to be in.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p02] See the section on bean scopes for more information.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p02] The return types of methods annotated with a bean scope annotation are the bean types.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p02] In this case, a `V8Engine` is created by the `EngineFactory` class' `v8Engine` method.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p02] Note that you can inject parameters into the method, and they will be resolved as beans.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p02] The resulting `V8Engine` bean will be a singleton.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p02] A factory can have multiple methods annotated with bean scope annotations, each one returning a distinct bean type.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p02] With Micronaut framework 3.0 or above it is also possible to produce beans from fields by declaring the @Bean annotation on a field.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p02] Whilst generally this approach should be discouraged in favour for factory methods, which provide more flexibility it does simplify testing code.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p02] Note that only public or package protected fields are supported on non-primitive types.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p02] If the field is `static`, `private`, or `protected` a compilation error will occur.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p02] Since Micronaut framework 3.1 it is possible to define and inject primitive types and array types from factories.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p02] Factory methods can throw DisabledBeanException to conditionally disable beans.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p02] Using @Requires should always be the preferred method to conditionally create beans; throwing an exception in a factory method should only be done if using @Requires is not possible.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p02] A common use case with factories is to take advantage of annotation metadata from the point at which an object is injected such that behaviour can be modified based on said metadata.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p02] The above `Vehicle` class specifies an annotation value of `@Cylinders(6)` indicating an `Engine` of six cylinders is required.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p02] At times, you may want a bean to load conditionally based on various potential factors including the classpath, the configuration, the presence of other beans, etc.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p02] The Requires annotation provides the ability to define one or many conditions on a bean.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p02] The above bean defines two requirements.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p02] The first indicates that a `DataSource` bean must be present for the bean to load.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p02] The second requirement ensures that the `datasource.url` property is set before loading the `JdbcBookService` bean.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p02] If you have multiple beans that need to fulfill a given requirement before loading, you may want to consider a bean configuration group, as explained in the next section.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p03] The @Requires annotation is very flexible and can be used for a variety of use cases.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p03] Adding a requirement on a property has some additional functionality.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p03] You can require the property to be a certain value, not be a certain value, and use a default in those checks if it is not set.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p03] You can also reference other beans properties in `@Requires` to conditionally load beans.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p03] Similar to `property` requirements, you can specify required `value` or set the value bean property should not be equal to using `notEquals` annotation member.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p03] For the bean property to be checked, the bean of type specified in `bean` annotation member should be present within context, otherwise conditional bean will not be loaded.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p03] Specified bean property is accessed through respective getter method whose presence and availability will be checked at compilation time.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p03] Note that bean property is considered to be present in case it’s value is not null.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p03] Keep in mind that primitive properties are initialized with default values such as `false` for boolean and `0` for int, so they are considered to be set even if no value is explicitly specified for them.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p03] If you have multiple conditions and complex requirements it may become difficult to understand why a particular bean has not been loaded.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p03] To help resolve issues with conditional beans you can enable debug logging for the `io.micronaut.context.condition` package which will log the reasons why beans were not loaded.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p03] Consult the logging chapter for details howto setup logging.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p03] One significant difference between Micronaut’s Dependency Injection system and Spring’s is the way beans are replaced.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p03] In a Spring application, beans have names and are overridden by creating a bean with the same name, regardless of the type of the bean.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p03] Spring also has the notion of bean registration order, hence in Spring Boot you have `@AutoConfigureBefore` and `@AutoConfigureAfter` annotations that control how beans override each other.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p03] To avoid these problems, Micronaut’s DI has no concept of bean names or load order.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p03] You cannot override a bean of a completely different type with another.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p03] A useful benefit of Spring’s approach is that it allows overriding existing beans to customize behaviour.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p03] To support the same ability, Micronaut’s DI provides an explicit @Replaces annotation, which integrates nicely with support for Conditional Beans and clearly documents and expresses the intention of the developer.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p03] Any existing bean can be replaced by another bean that declares @Replaces.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p03] The `@Replaces` annotation also supports a `factory` argument.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p03] That argument allows the replacement of factory beans in their entirety or specific types created by the factory.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p03] In this example, `BookFactory#textBook()` is **not** replaced because this factory does not have a factory method that returns a `TextBook`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p03] To replace one or more factory methods but retain the rest, apply the `@Replaces` annotation on the method(s) and denote the factory to apply to.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p03] The `BookFactory#novel()` method will not be replaced because the TextBook class is defined in the annotation.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p03] When exposing an API, you may want to define an implementation of the interface that is used as the default when injecting a particular interface.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p03] For this you can use the @DefaultImplementation annotation.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p03] It may also be desirable to not expose the default implementation of an interface as part of the public API by making it package private in Java.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p03] Doing so prevents users from being able to replace the implementation because they will not be able to reference the class.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p03] The @DefaultImplementation annotation allows the framework to establish the implementation to replace if a user creates a bean that declares `@Replaces(YourInterface.class)`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p03] In the above example, the `CustomResponseStrategy` replaces the `DefaultResponseStrategy` because the DefaultImplementation annotation points to the `DefaultResponseStrategy`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p03] A bean @Configuration is a grouping of multiple bean definitions within a package.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p03] The `@Configuration` annotation is applied at the package level and informs the Micronaut framework that the beans defined with the package form a logical grouping.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p03] The `@Configuration` annotation is typically applied to `package-info` classes.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p03] Where this grouping becomes useful is when the bean configuration is made conditional via the `@Requires` annotation.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p03] In the above example, all bean definitions within the annotated package are only loaded and made available if a `javax.sql.DataSource` bean is present.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p03] This lets you implement conditional autoconfiguration of bean definitions.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p03] To manage when a bean is constructed, see the section on bean scopes.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p03] For factory beans, the `preDestroy` value in the Bean annotation tells Micronaut framework which method to invoke.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p03] Dependent beans are the beans used in the construction of your bean.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p03] If the dependent bean’s scope is `@Prototype` or unknown, it will be destroyed along with your instance.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p03] In some deployments, it is desirable to "gracefully" shut down an application, that is, to stop accepting new work but to finish in-progress tasks.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p03] If the `micronaut.lifecycle.graceful-shutdown.enabled` config property is set to `true`, a graceful shutdown is triggered automatically when the context stops (`ApplicationContext.stop()`).
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p03] There is also a programmatic GracefulShutdownManager API if you want more control over the shutdown process.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p03] Graceful shutdown status can be read using the health management endpoint.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p03] This also returns the number of still-active tasks (e.g. connections or running scheduled tasks).
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p03] If you want to add graceful shutdown support to your own beans, implement GracefulShutdownCapable.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p03] You will implement a `shutdownGracefully` method that triggers shutdown and returns a future that should complete once the graceful shutdown is complete (e.g. all clients have closed their connection).
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p03] You can also optionally implement `reportActiveTasks` to give a number of active tasks for the health endpoint.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p03] The Micronaut framework supports a general event system through the context.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p03] The ApplicationEventPublisher API publishes events and the ApplicationEventListener API is used to listen to events.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p03] The event system is not limited to events that Micronaut publishes and supports custom events created by users.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p03] `micronaut-context` is a transitive dependency of `micronaut-http`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p03] If you use a Micronaut HTTP runtime, your project already includes the `Micronaut-context` dependency.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p03] The ApplicationEventPublisher API supports events of any type, although all events that the Micronaut framework publishes extend ApplicationEvent.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p03] To publish an event, use dependency injection to obtain an instance of ApplicationEventPublisher where the generic type is the type of event and invoke the `publishEvent` method with your event object.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p03] To listen to an event, register a bean that implements ApplicationEventListener where the generic type is the type of event.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p03] The event listener by default runs on the `scheduled` executor.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p03] The `BeanInitializedEventListener` interface is commonly used in combination with Factory beans.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p03] The BeanCreatedEventListener interface is more typically used to decorate or enhance a fully initialized bean, for example by creating a proxy.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p03] Since Micronaut framework 1.1, a compile-time replacement for the JDK’s Introspector class has been included.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p03] The BeanIntrospector and BeanIntrospection interfaces allow looking up bean introspections to instantiate and read/write bean properties without using reflection or caching reflective metadata, which consume excessive memory for large beans.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p03] Unlike the JDK’s Introspector, every class is not automatically available for introspection.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p03] To make a class available for introspection you must at a minimum enable Micronaut’s annotation processor (`micronaut-inject-java` for Java and Kotlin and `micronaut-inject-groovy` for Groovy) in your build and ensure you have a runtime time dependency on `micronaut-core`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p03] Once your build is configured you have a few ways to generate introspection data.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p03] The @Introspected annotation can be used on any class to make it available for introspection.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p03] It’s possible to apply the introspection to all the classes in one package.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p03] Simply create `package-info` file and annotate the package with @Introspected.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p04] By default, Java introspections treat only JavaBean getters/setters or Java 16 record components as bean properties.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p04] The @Property annotation can be used on an introspected field or method to make that member an explicit bean property.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p04] This is useful when the member does not follow normal JavaBean getter or setter naming rules, or when the property should expose extra metadata such as an external serialized name.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p04] In the example above, `title()` and `title(String)` are included as read/write bean property accessors even though they are not JavaBean `getTitle` and `setTitle` methods.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p04] The `author()` method is included as a read-only property because its `accessKind` only contains `Introspected.Property.Access.READ`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p04] The `value` member is a shorthand for `name`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p04] The `name` member represents an external property name and is available through the property annotation metadata.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p04] It does not change the Micronaut bean property name used with BeanIntrospection lookup methods.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p04] If both `value` and `name` are declared, they must contain the same value.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p04] If both a getter and setter exist, Micronaut can still expose a read/write property.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p04] Use `accessKind` when a field or method must restrict one side of access, for example read-only or write-only properties.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p04] The access declaration applies to the whole bean property.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p04] Multiple @Property declarations for the same bean property must declare the same `accessKind`; conflicting declarations are rejected during compilation.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p04] When @Property is declared on a field that belongs to the same bean property as getter or setter methods, Micronaut uses the normal bean accessor precedence: getter methods are used for reads and setter methods are used for writes when they are present.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p04] The annotated field still contributes the mapped property metadata and can provide field access when a corresponding getter or setter is absent.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p04] Set `ignoreOtherAccessors` to `true` when the annotated member must be used for its access direction even if another field, getter, or setter exists for the same bean property.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p04] For example, an annotated field with the default read/write `accessKind` will be used for both reads and writes instead of same-name getter and setter methods.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p04] This means Jackson-style property names are visible through Micronaut bean property annotation metadata, and Jackson-annotated methods that do not follow JavaBean naming rules can still be recognized as bean properties.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p04] The `displayName` methods are treated as a bean property, and the external name `display_name` is available from the mapped @Property metadata.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p04] For `JsonGetter` and `JsonSetter`, read and write availability is determined by the available bean property reader and writer.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p04] Jackson annotations do not set `ignoreOtherAccessors`, so Micronaut keeps the same accessor precedence as Jackson Databind: getters are preferred for reads and setters are preferred for writes when they exist.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p04] Because `accessKind` is property-level, multiple Jackson annotations that map to the same bean property must agree on the mapped access.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p04] For classes with multiple constructors, apply the @Creator annotation to the constructor to use.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p04] The @Creator annotation can be applied to static methods that create class instances.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p04] If a type can only be constructed via the builder pattern then you can use the `builder` member of the @Introspected annotation to generate a dynamic builder.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p04] It is possible to introspect enums as well.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p04] Add the annotation to the enum, and it can be constructed through the standard `valueOf` method.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p04] If the class to introspect is already compiled and not under your control, an alternative option is to define a configuration class with the `classes` member of the @Introspected annotation set.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p04] In the above example the `PersonConfiguration` class generates introspections for the `Person` class.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p04] If there is an existing annotation that you wish to introspect by default you can write an AnnotationMapper.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p04] An example of this is EntityIntrospectedAnnotationMapper which ensures all beans annotated with `javax.persistence.Entity` are introspectable by default.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p04] A BeanProperty provides raw access to read and write a property value for a given class and does not provide any automatic type conversion.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p04] It is expected that the values you pass to the `set` and `get` methods match the underlying property type, otherwise an exception will occur.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p04] To provide additional type conversion smarts the BeanWrapper interface allows wrapping an existing bean instance and setting and getting properties from the bean, plus performing type conversion as necessary.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p04] Since 4.1.x the @Mapper annotation can be used on any abstract method to automatically create a mapping between one type and another.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p04] Since 4.8.x the annotation can also be used for merging beans.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p04] Inspired by similar functionality in libraries like Map Struct, a `Mapper` uses the Bean Introspection and Expressions features, built into the Micronaut Framework, which are already reflection free.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p04] You can write an interface to define a mapping between both types by simply annotating a method with @Mapper.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p04] The Micronaut compiler generates an implementation the previous an interface at compilation-time.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p04] You can then inject a bean of type `ContactMappers` and easily map from one type to another.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p04] Each abstract method can define a single @Mapper annotation or one or many @Mapping annotations to define how properties map onto the target type.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p04] It is common to want to alter this type’s representation in HTTP responses.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p04] Here the `price` property is of a different type and an extra property exists called `distributor`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p04] The `from` member can be used to define either a property name on the source type or an expression that reads values from the method argument and transforms them in whatever way you choose, including invoking other methods of the instance.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p04] You can retrieve from the context or inject a bean of type `ProductMappers`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p04] You can write an interface and method to merge the types by simply specifying two or more arguments to the method and annotating the method with @Mapper.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p04] Optionally, define custom mapping rules using @Mapping.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p04] You can then inject the type `ChristmasMappers` and easily merge the types.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p04] See more mapping examples in the following snippet.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p04] See the Micronaut Validation documentation.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p04] The methods provided by Java’s AnnotatedElement API in general don’t provide the ability to introspect annotations without loading the annotations themselves.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p04] Nor do they provide any ability to introspect annotation stereotypes (often called meta-annotations; an annotation stereotype is where an annotation is annotated with another annotation, essentially inheriting its behaviour).
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p04] To solve this problem many frameworks produce runtime metadata or perform expensive reflection to analyze the annotations of a class.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p04] The Micronaut framework instead produces this annotation metadata at compile time, avoiding expensive reflection and saving memory.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p04] The BeanContext API can be used to obtain a reference to a BeanDefinition which implements the AnnotationMetadata interface.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p04] The above example finds all BeanDefinition instances annotated with `@Controller` whether `@Controller` is used directly or inherited via an annotation stereotype.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p04] Note that the `getAnnotation` method and the variations of the method return an AnnotationValue type and not a Java annotation.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p04] This is by design, and you should generally try to work with this API when reading annotation values, since synthesizing a proxy implementation is worse from a performance and memory consumption perspective.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p04] This approach is not recommended however, as it requires reflection and increases memory consumption due to the use of runtime generated proxies, and should be used as a last resort, for example if you need an instance of the annotation to integrate with a third-party library.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p04] In general behaviour which you may wish to override is not inherited by default including Bean Scopes, Bean Qualifiers, Bean Conditions, Validation Rules and so on.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p04] If you wish a particular scope, qualifier, or set of requirements to be inherited when subclassing then you can define a meta-annotation that is annotated with `@Inherited`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p04] There are times when you may want to alias the value of an annotation member to the value of another annotation member.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p04] To do this, use the @AliasFor annotation.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p04] With these aliases in place, whether you define `@Client("foo")` or `@Client(id="foo")`, both the `value` and `id` members will be set, making it easier to parse and work with the annotation.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p04] If you do not have control over the annotation, another approach is to use an AnnotationMapper.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p04] The following is an example `AnnotationMapper` that improves the introspection capabilities of JPA entities.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p04] You can use the @Import annotation to import beans from external, already compiled libraries that use JSR-330 annotations.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p04] As an alternative to the @Import annotation the @ClassImport annotation allows to process already compiled classes as if they were ordinary non-compiled classes.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p04] Internally all the type visitors will be run, allowing to create necessary metadata.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p04] In the same way, it’s possible to import classes required for Micronaut Serialization or Micronaut Validation.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p05] The most used scenario is to modify the annotations when the class is imported with @ClassImport or a scenario when classes are generated and cannot be modified.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p05] It’s possible to define a mixin class by annotating it with @Mixin and specifying which class does it reference.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p05] All the annotations of the mixin will be copied to the original class and all the annotations of the constructor with matching parameters, fields of the same name and methods of the same name with matching parameters will be copied.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p05] The mixin supports copying only specific annotations by defining `includeAnnotations`, the set of annotations or packages that should be copied.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p05] Alternatively there is `excludeAnnotation` that will copy only annotations not excluded.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p05] Each mixin point (constructor, method, field, parameter) can have specific rules of copying using @Filter.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p05] The annotation @Filter also support removing existing annotations of the original class.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p05] In Java, you can use annotations showing whether a variable can or cannot be null.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p05] Such annotations aren’t part of the standard library.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p05] These annotations are designed for use on parameters, return values, fields, and type-use positions (for example, generic type arguments).
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p05] Throughout the history of the framework, we used other nullability annotation libraries.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p05] However, licensing issues made us change nullability annotations several times.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p05] Kotlin does not recognize Micronaut framework’s nullability annotations.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p05] However, Micronaut supports other nullability annotations via AnnotationMapper.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p05] To better support Kotlin, we recommended to use JSpecify or any other Kotlin recognizable nullability annotations.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p05] Micronaut supports JSpecify annotations as an alternative to its own.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p05] Internally they are simply remapped to the Micronaut ones.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p05] Micronaut framework has integrations with Spring in several forms.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p05] See the Micronaut Spring Documentation for more information.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p05] Since Micronaut dependency injection is based on annotation processors and doesn’t rely on reflection, it can be used on Android when using the Android plugin 3.0.0 or higher.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p05] This lets you use the same application framework for both your Android client and server implementation.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p05] To get started, add the Micronaut annotation processors to the processor classpath using the `annotationProcessor` dependency configuration.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p05] You can find more information on configuring annotations processors in the Android documentation.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p05] Once you have configured the classpath correctly, the next step is start the ApplicationContext.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p05] Micronaut features a flexible configuration mechanism that allows reading configuration from a variety of sources into a unified model that can be bound to Java types annotated with @ConfigurationProperties.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p05] Configuration can by default be provided in Java properties files or JSON with the ability to add support for more formats (such as YAML or Groovy configuration) by adding additional third-party libraries to your classpath.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p05] In addition, Micronaut framework allows overriding any property via system properties or environment variables.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p05] Each source of configuration is modeled with the PropertySource interface and the mechanism is extensible, allowing the implementation of additional PropertySourceLoader implementations.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p05] Micronaut also supports in-file configuration imports via `micronaut.config.import`, which allows one configuration source to load additional sources recursively.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p05] See Property Sources for protocol-specific syntax (`file`, `classpath`, `env`, `configtree`) and optional import behavior.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p05] The application environment is modelled by the Environment interface, which allows specifying one or many unique environment names when creating an ApplicationContext.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p05] The active environment names allow loading different configuration files depending on the environment, and also using the @Requires annotation to conditionally load beans or bean @Configuration packages.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p05] In addition, the Micronaut framework attempts to detect the current environments.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p05] For example within a Spock or JUnit test the TEST environment is automatically active.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p05] Additional active environments can be specified using the `micronaut.environments` system property or the `MICRONAUT_ENVIRONMENTS` environment variable.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p05] These are specified as a comma-separated list.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p05] The above activates environments called `foo` and `bar`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p05] It is also possible to enable the detection of the Cloud environment the application is deployed to (this feature is disabled by default since Micronaut framework 4).
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p05] See the section on Cloud Configuration for more information.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p05] The Micronaut framework loads property sources based on the environments specified, and if the same property key exists in multiple property sources specific to an environment, the environment order determines which value to use.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p05] Automatic detection of environments can be disabled by setting the `micronaut.env.deduction` system property or the `MICRONAUT_ENV_DEDUCTION` environment variable to `false`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p05] This prevents the Micronaut framework from detecting current environments, while still using any environments that are specifically provided as shown above.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p05] Alternatively, you can disable environment deduction using the ApplicationContextBuilder `deduceEnvironment` method when setting up your application.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p05] The Micronaut framework supports the concept of one or many default environments.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p05] A default environment is one that is only applied if no other environments are explicitly specified or deduced.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p05] Environments can be explicitly specified either through the application context builder `Micronaut.build().environments(…)`, through the `micronaut.environments` system property, or the `MICRONAUT_ENVIRONMENTS` environment variable.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p05] Environments can be deduced to automatically apply the environment appropriate for cloud deployments.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p05] If an environment is found through any of the above means, the default environment will **not** be applied.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p05] Since Micronaut framework 2.3 a banner is shown when the application starts.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p05] It is enabled by default, and it also shows the Micronaut version.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p05] To customize the banner with your own ASCII Art (just plain ASCII at this moment), create the file `src/main/resources/micronaut-banner.txt` and it will be used instead.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p06] Additional PropertySource instances can be added to the environment prior to initializing the ApplicationContext.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p06] The PropertySource.of method can be used to create a `PropertySource` from a map of values.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p06] Alternatively one can register a PropertySourceLoader by creating a `META-INF/services/io.micronaut.context.env.PropertySourceLoader` file containing a reference to the class name of the `PropertySourceLoader`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p06] Configuration files loaded in order from the system property 'micronaut.config.files' or the environment variable `MICRONAUT_CONFIG_FILES`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p06] The value can be a comma-separated list of paths with the last file having precedence.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p06] The files can be referenced from: the file system as an absolute path (without any prefix), the classpath with a `classpath:` prefix.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p06] You can import additional configuration directly from a configuration file using `micronaut.config.import`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p06] The value can be a single string, a list, or indexed entries (`micronaut.config.import[0]`, `micronaut.config.import[1]`, …).
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p06] Prefix any import with `optional:` to skip it when the target is missing.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p06] Without `optional:`, an ConfigurationException is thrown if the import cannot be loaded.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p06] For `file://`, `classpath://`, and `classpath*://` imports, if no extension is provided, Micronaut probes known configuration extensions (`.properties`, `.json`, `.yml`, and any additional enabled loaders).
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p06] For `env://` imports, Micronaut defaults to `.properties` parsing.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p06] To import YAML or JSON from an environment variable, either include the format in the variable reference such as `env://MY_APP_INLINE_CONFIG.yml`, or specify it explicitly with `env://MY_APP_INLINE_CONFIG?extension=yml`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p06] You can add support for a custom import protocol by implementing PropertySourceImporter and registering it with Java ServiceLoader.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p06] Each importer declares its provider with `getProvider()`, converts the parsed ConnectionString into a typed declaration via `newImportDeclaration(..)`, and then reads configuration from `importPropertySource(..)`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p06] After registration, the importer is selected when `micronaut.config.import` uses your protocol, for example `demo://defaults`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p06] If your importer loads remote configuration, RetryablePropertySourceImporter in `micronaut-discovery-core` provides a reusable base class that standardizes retry behavior across both connection-string and map-based imports.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p06] It parses the same retry properties from either form and applies them with Micronaut’s programmatic retry support.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p06] The behavior can be customized using the ApplicationContextBuilder (including `Micronaut`).
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p06] Note that if you want full control of where your application loads configuration from you can disable the default `PropertySourceLoader` implementations listed above by calling the `enableDefaultPropertySources(false)` method of the ApplicationContextBuilder interface when starting your application.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p06] In this case only explicit PropertySource instances that you add via the `propertySources(..)` method of the ApplicationContextBuilder interface will be used.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p06] Configuration can be supplied at the command line using Gradle or our Maven plugin.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p06] For the configuration to be a part of the context, the args from the main method must be passed to the context builder.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p06] It is important to note that it is not recommended to store sensitive configuration such as passwords and tokens within configuration files that can potentially be checked into source control systems.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p06] It is good practise to instead externalize sensitive configuration completely from the application code using preferably an external secret manager system (there are many options here, many provided by Cloud providers) or environment variables that are set during the deployment of the application.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p06] As mentioned in the previous section, the Micronaut framework includes a property placeholder syntax to reference configuration properties both within configuration values and with any Micronaut annotation.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p06] See @Value and the section on Configuration Injection.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p06] The basic syntax is to wrap a reference to a property in `${…}`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p06] The above example embeds references to the `micronaut.server.host` and `micronaut.server.port` properties.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p06] You can specify default values by defining a value after the `:` character.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p06] The above example defaults to `localhost` and port `8080` if no value is found (rather than throwing an exception).
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p06] The above example looks for a `server.address` property and defaults to `http://localhost:8080`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p06] This default value is escaped with backticks since it has a `:` character.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p06] Note that these property references should be in kebab case (lowercase and hyphen-separated) when placing references in code or in placeholder values.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p06] For example, use `micronaut.server.default-charset` and not `micronaut.server.defaultCharset`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p06] The Micronaut framework still allows specifying the latter in configuration, but normalizes the properties into kebab case form to optimize memory consumption and reduce complexity when resolving properties.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p06] Environment variables are treated specially to allow more flexibility.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p06] Note that there is no way to reference an environment variable with camel-case.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p06] To control how environment properties participate in configuration, call the respective methods on the `Micronaut` builder.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p06] You can use `random` values by using the following properties.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p06] These can be used in configuration files as variables like the following.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p06] For beans that inject required properties, the injection and potential failure will not occur until the bean is requested.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p06] To verify at startup that the properties exist and can be injected, the bean can be annotated with @Context.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p06] Context-scoped beans are injected at startup, and startup fails if any required properties are missing or cannot be converted to the required type.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p06] You can inject configuration values into beans using the @Value annotation.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p06] Note that `@Value` can also be used to inject a static value.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p06] This is even more useful when used to compose injected values combining static content and placeholders.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p06] In the above example the URL is constructed from two placeholder properties that must be present in configuration: `my.host` and `my.port`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p06] Remember that to specify a default value in a placeholder expression, you use the colon `:` character.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p06] However, if the default you specify includes a colon, you must escape the value with backticks.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p06] Note that there is nothing special about `@Value` itself regarding the resolution of property value placeholders.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p06] Due to Micronaut’s extensive support for annotation metadata you can use property placeholder expressions on any annotation.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p06] In the above case, if `hello.controller.path` is specified in configuration the controller will be mapped to the specified path, otherwise it will be mapped to `/hello`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p06] In the above example the property `my.server.url` can be used to configure the client, otherwise the client falls back to a localhost address.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p06] Recall that the @Value annotation receives a String value which can be a mix of static content and placeholder expressions.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p06] In the above case the literal string value `my.url` is injected and set to the `url` field and **not** the value of the `my.url` property from your application configuration.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p06] This is because `@Value` only resolves placeholders within the value specified to it.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p06] The above instead injects the value of the `my.engine.cylinders` property resolved from application configuration.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p06] If the property cannot be found in configuration, an exception is thrown.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p06] As with other types of injection, the injection point can also be annotated with `@Nullable` to make the injection optional.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p06] You can also use this feature to resolve sub maps.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p06] The injected map will contain the keys `hibernate.hbm2ddl.auto` and `hibernate.show_sql` and their values.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p06] Since 4.0, Micronaut framework supports embedding evaluated expressions in annotation values using `#{…}` syntax which allows to achieve even more flexibility while configuring your application.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p06] Expressions can be defined whenever an annotation member accepts a string or an array of strings.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p06] You can also embed one or more expressions in a string template in a similar manner to embedding properties with the `${…}` syntax.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p06] Evaluated Expressions are validated and compiled at build time which guarantees type safety at runtime.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p06] Once an application is running expressions are evaluated on demand as part of annotation metadata resolution.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p06] The usage of expressions does not impact performance as evaluation process is completely reflection free.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p06] Note that, for security reasons expressions cannot be dynamically compiled at runtime from potentially untrusted input.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p06] All expressions are compiled and checked statically during the compilation process of the application with errors reported as compilation failures.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p06] In general, expressions can be treated as statement written using a programming language with reduced set of available features.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p06] Even though the complexity of expression is only limited by the list of supported syntax constructs, it is in general not recommended to place complex logic inside an expression as there are usually better ways to achieve the same result.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] Integer and Long values can also be specified in hexadecimal or octal notation.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] Float and Double values can also be specified in exponential notation.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] All numeric values can be negative as well.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] Math operators can only be applied to numeric values (except ` which can be used for string concatenation as well).
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] Mathematical operations are performed in order enforced by standard operator precedence.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] You can also change evaluation order by using brackets `()`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] `/` and `%` operators can be aliased by `div` and `mod` keywords respectively.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] The following comparison operators are supported: `==`, `!=`, `>`, `<`, `>=`, `<=`, `matches` Comparison operations are performed in order enforced by standard operator precedence.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] Equality check is supported for both primitive types and objects.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] It is performed using `Object.equals()` method.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] `>`, `<`, `>=`, `<=` operations can be applied to numeric types or types that implement `java.lang.Comparable` interface.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] `matches` keyword can be used to determine whether a string matches provided regular expression which has to be specified as string literal.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] The regular expression itself will be checked for validity at compilation time.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] Logical operations are performed in order enforced by standard operator precedence.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] where `condition` evaluation should provide boolean value, and the complexity of `then` and `else` branches is not limited.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] The dot operator can be used to access methods and properties of a value within an expression.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] A predefined syntax construct `T(…)` can be used to reference a class.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] The value inside brackets should be fully qualified class name (including the package name).
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] The only exception is `java.lang.*` classes which can be referenced directly by only specifying the simple class name.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] Type References are evaluated in different ways depending on the context.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] A simple type reference is resolved as a `Class<?>` object.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] Same rule applies if type reference is specified as a method argument.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] By default, the only methods you can invoke inside Evaluated Expressions are static methods using type references.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] The available methods can be extended by extended the evaluation context.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] There are two ways to extend the evaluation context.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] The first involves registering new context class via a custom TypeElementVisitor.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] Once a class is registered within evaluation context the methods and properties of the class are available for referencing in evaluated expressions.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] At runtime, the bean will be retrieved from application context and respective method will be invoked.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] If a matching method is not found within evaluation context at compilation time, the compilation will fail.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] A compilation error will also occur if multiple suitable methods are found in the evaluation context, keep that in mind if you provide multiple ExpressionEvaluationContextRegistrar that a conflict can occur as these types are effectively global.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] The methods will be considered ambiguous (leading to compilation failure) when their names are the same and list of provided arguments matches multiple methods parameters.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] Using a ExpressionEvaluationContextRegistrar makes its methods and properties available for evaluated expressions within any annotation in a global manner.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] However, you can also specify evaluation context scoped to concrete annotation or annotation member using @AnnotationExpressionContext.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] Again context classes need to be explicitly defined as beans to make them available for retrieval from application context at runtime.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] You can invoke both static methods using type references, methods from evaluation context and methods on objects, which means method chaining is supported.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] Varargs methods invocation is supported as well.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] Note that if last parameter of a method is an array, you can still invoke it providing list of arguments separated by comma without explicitly wrapping it into array.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] So in this case it will be treated in same way as if last method argument was explicitly specified as varargs parameter.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] JavaBean properties can be accessed simply be referencing their names from evaluation context prefixed with `#`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] Bean properties can also be chained with dot in the same way as methods.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] A predefined syntax construct `ctx[…]` can be used to retrieve beans from bean context.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] The argument inside square brackets has to be a fully qualified class name (note that `T(…)` wrapper is optional and can be omitted for simplicity).
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] A syntax construct `env[…]` can be used to retrieve environment properties by name.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] The expression inside square brackets has to resolve to string value, otherwise compilation will fail.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] You can create type-safe configuration by creating classes that are annotated with @ConfigurationProperties.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] The Micronaut framework will produce a reflection-free `@ConfigurationProperties` bean and will also at compile time calculate the property paths to evaluate, greatly improving the speed and efficiency of loading `@ConfigurationProperties`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] Configuration values can then be supplied from one of the PropertySource instances.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] Note for more complex configurations you can structure @ConfigurationProperties beans through inheritance.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] For example creating a subclass of `EngineConfig` with `@ConfigurationProperties('bar')` will resolve all properties under the path `my.engine.bar`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] For the cases where the configuration properties class inherits properties from a parent class, it may be desirable to exclude properties from the parent class.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] The `includes` and `excludes` members of the @ConfigurationProperties annotation allow for that functionality.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] The list applies to both local properties and inherited properties.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] The names supplied to the includes/excludes list must be the "property" name.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] For example if a setter method is injected, the property name is the de-capitalized setter name (`setConnectionTimeout` → `connectionTimeout`).
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] Since 3.3, the Micronaut framework supports defining different accessors prefixes for getters and setter other than the default `get` and `set` defined for Java Beans.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] Annotate your POJO or `@ConfigurationProperties` class with the @AccessorsStyle annotation.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] This is useful when you write the getters and setters in a fluent way.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] Now you can inject `EngineConfig` and use it with `engineConfig.manufacturer()` and `engineConfig.cylinders()` to retrieve the values from configuration.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] The Micronaut framework uses the ConversionService bean to convert values when resolving properties.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] You can register additional converters for types not supported by Micronaut by defining beans that implement the TypeConverter interface.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] The Micronaut framework features some built-in conversions that are useful, which are detailed below.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] Durations can be specified by appending the unit with a number.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] Lists and arrays can be specified in Java properties files as comma-separated values, or in YAML using native YAML lists.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] The generic types are used to convert the values.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] You can annotate any setter parameter with @ReadableBytes to allow the value to be set using a shorthand syntax for specifying bytes, kilobytes etc.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] The @Format annotation can be used on setters to specify the date format to use when binding `java.time` date objects.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] Many frameworks and tools already use builder-style classes to construct configuration.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] You can use the @ConfigurationBuilder annotation to populate a builder-style class with configuration values.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] ConfigurationBuilder can be applied to fields or methods in a class annotated with @ConfigurationProperties.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] Since there is no consistent way to define builders in the Java world, one or more method prefixes can be specified in the annotation to support builder methods like `withXxx` or `setXxx`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] If the builder methods have no prefix, assign an empty string to the parameter.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] A configuration prefix can also be specified to tell the Micronaut framework where to look for configuration values.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] By default, builder methods use the configuration prefix specified in a class-level @ConfigurationProperties annotation.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] Like in the previous example, we can construct an `EngineImpl`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] Since we are using a builder, we can use a factory class to build the engine from the builder.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] The engine that was returned can then be injected anywhere an engine is required.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] Configuration values can be supplied from one of the PropertySource instances.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] For some use cases it may be desirable to accept a map of arbitrary configuration properties that can be supplied to a bean, especially if the bean represents a third-party API where not all the possible configuration properties are known.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] For example, a datasource may accept a map of configuration properties specific to a particular database driver, allowing the user to specify any desired options in the map without coding each property explicitly.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] For this purpose, the MapFormat annotation lets you bind a map to a single configuration property, and specify whether to accept a flat map of keys to values, or a nested map (where the values may be additional maps).
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] Now a map of properties can be supplied to the `my.engine.sensors` configuration property.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] The Micronaut framework includes an extensible type conversion mechanism.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] To add additional type converters you register beans of type TypeConverter.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] The following example shows how to use one of the built-in converters (Map to an Object) or create your own.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] The type `MyConfigurationProperties` has a property named `updatedAt` of type LocalDate.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p07] This won’t work by default, since there is no built-in conversion from `Map` to `LocalDate`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p08] The @ConfigurationProperties annotation is great for a single configuration class, but sometimes you want multiple instances, each with its own distinct configuration.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p08] The @EachProperty annotation creates a `ConfigurationProperties` bean for each sub-property within the given name.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p08] The above `DataSourceConfiguration` defines a `url` property to configure one or more data sources.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p08] In the above example two data sources (called `one` and `two`) are defined under the `test.datasource` prefix defined earlier in the `@EachProperty` annotation.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p08] The default behavior of @EachProperty is to bind from a map style of configuration, where the key is the named qualifier of the bean and the value is the data to bind from.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p08] For cases where map style configuration doesn’t make sense, it is possible to inform the Micronaut framework that the class is bound from a list.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p08] Simply set the `list` member on the annotation to true.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p08] The @EachProperty annotation is a great way to drive dynamic configuration, but typically you want to inject that configuration into another bean that depends on it.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p08] Since 1.3, Micronaut framework supports the definition of immutable configuration.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p08] Immutable configuration with an interface requires the Micronaut Context dependency.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p08] There are two ways to define immutable configuration.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p08] The preferred way is to define an interface annotated with @ConfigurationProperties.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p08] In this case the Micronaut framework provides a compile-time implementation that delegates all getters to call the `getProperty(..)` method of the Environment interface.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p08] This has the advantage that if the application configuration is refreshed (for example by invoking the `/refresh` endpoint), the injected interface automatically sees the new values.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p08] Another way to implement immutable configuration is to define a class and use the @ConfigurationInject annotation on a constructor of a @ConfigurationProperties or @EachProperty bean.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p08] The @ConfigurationInject annotation provides a hint to the Micronaut framework to prioritize binding values from configuration instead of injecting beans.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p08] There are a few exceptions to this rule.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p08] Configuration values can then be supplied when running the application.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p08] For Java language applications, it’s also possible to use Java Record Classes for immutable configuration with @ConfigurationProperties.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p08] Most application configuration is stored in your configuration file (e.g `application.yml`), environment-specific files like `application-{environment}.{extension}`, environment and system properties, etc.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p08] These configure the application context.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p08] But during application startup, before the application context is created, a "bootstrap" context can be created to store configuration necessary to retrieve additional configuration for the main context.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p08] Typically, that additional configuration is in some remote source.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p08] The bootstrap context is enabled depending on the following conditions.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p08] Configuration properties that must be present before application context configuration properties are resolved, for example when using distributed configuration, are stored in a bootstrap configuration file.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p08] Once it is determined the bootstrap context is enabled (as described above), the bootstrap configuration files are read using the same rules as regular application configuration.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p08] See the property source documentation for the details.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p08] The only difference is the prefix (`bootstrap` instead of `application`).
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p08] The file name prefix `bootstrap` is configurable with a system property micronaut.bootstrap.name.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p08] That means if a configuration property is needed in both places, it should go into the bootstrap context configuration.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p08] See the distributed configuration section of the documentation for the list of integrations with common distributed configuration solutions.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p08] In order for a bean to be resolvable in the bootstrap context it must be annotated with @BootstrapContextCompatible.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p08] If any given bean is not annotated then it will not be able to be resolved in the bootstrap context.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p08] Typically, any bean that is participating in the process of retrieving distributed configuration needs to be annotated.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p08] Micronaut framework provides basic support for JMX.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p08] For more information, see the documentation for the micronaut-jmx project.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p08] Aspect-Oriented Programming (AOP) has historically had many incarnations and some very complicated implementations.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p08] Generally AOP can be thought of as a way to define cross-cutting concerns (logging, transactions, tracing, etc.) separate from application code in the form of aspects that define advice.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p08] In modern Java applications, declaring advice typically takes the form of an annotation.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p08] The most well-known annotation advice in the Java world is probably `@Transactional`, which demarcates transaction boundaries in Spring and Grails applications.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p08] The disadvantage of traditional approaches to AOP is the heavy reliance on runtime proxy creation and reflection, which slows application performance, makes debugging harder and increases memory consumption.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p08] Micronaut framework tries to address these concerns by providing a simple compile-time AOP API that does not use reflection.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p08] The most common type of advice you may want to apply is "Around" advice, which lets you decorate a method’s behaviour.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p08] The next step to defining Around advice is to implement a MethodInterceptor.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p08] Whenever the type `NotNullExample` is injected into a class, a compile-time-generated proxy is injected that decorates method calls with the `@NotNull` advice defined earlier.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p08] You can verify that the advice works by writing a test.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p08] The default behaviour of the Around annotation is to generate a proxy at compile time that is a subclass of the proxied class.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p08] In other words, in the previous example a compile-time subclass of the `NotNullExample` class will be produced where proxied methods are decorated with interceptor handling, and the original behaviour is invoked via a call to `super`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p08] This behaviour is more efficient as only one instance of the bean is required, however depending on the use case you may wish to alter this behaviour.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p08] AOP advice applied on a method annotated with a bean scope applies the AOP advice to the bean that the factory produces.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p08] The above example logs the time it takes to create the `MyBean` bean.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p08] The above example logs the time it takes to execute the public methods of the `MyBean` bean, but not the bean creation.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p08] The rationale for this behaviour is that you may at times wish to apply advice to a factory and at other times apply advice to the bean produced by the factory.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p08] Note that there is currently no way to apply advice at the method level to a @Factory bean, and all advice for factories must be applied at the type level.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p08] You can control which methods have advice applied by defining methods as non-public which do not have advice applied.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p08] Introduction advice is distinct from Around advice in that it involves providing an implementation instead of decorating.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p08] Examples of introduction advice includes Spring Data which implements persistence logic for you.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p08] Micronaut Client annotation is another example of introduction advice where the Micronaut framework implements HTTP client interfaces for you at compile time.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p08] The way you implement Introduction advice is very similar to how you implement Around advice.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p08] You start by defining an annotation that powers the introduction advice.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p08] As an example, say you want to implement advice to return a stubbed value for every method in an interface (a common requirement in testing frameworks).
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p08] The `StubIntroduction` class referred to in the previous example must then implement the MethodInterceptor interface, just like around advice.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p08] All abstract methods delegate to the `StubIntroduction` class to be implemented.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p08] Note that if the introduction advice cannot implement the method, call the `proceed` method of the MethodInvocationContext.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p08] This lets other introduction advice interceptors implement the method, and an `UnsupportedOperationException` will be thrown if no advice can implement the method.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p08] In addition, if multiple introduction advice are present you may wish to override the `getOrder()` method of MethodInterceptor to control the priority of advice.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p08] The following sections cover core advice types provided by Micronaut.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] There are cases where you want to introduce a new bean based on the presence of an annotation on a method.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] An example of this is the @EventListener annotation which produces an implementation of ApplicationEventListener for each annotated method that invokes the annotated method.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] The presence of the @EventListener annotation causes the Micronaut framework to create a new class that implements ApplicationEventListener and invokes the `onStartup` method defined in the bean above.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] Using this mechanism you can define custom annotations that use the @Adapter annotation and a SAM interface to automatically implement beans for you at compile time.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] Sometimes you may need to apply advice to a bean’s lifecycle.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] The Micronaut framework supports these 3 use cases by allowing the definition of additional @InterceptorBinding meta-annotations.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] Note that if you do not need `@PostConstruct` and `@PreDestroy` interception you can simply remove those bindings.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] Now you can define ConstructorInterceptor beans for constructor interception and MethodInterceptor beans for `@PostConstruct` or `@PreDestroy` interception.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] Defining MethodInterceptor instances that interceptor the `@PostConstruct` and `@PreDestroy` methods is no different from defining interceptors for regular methods.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] Validation advice is one of the most common advice types you are likely to want to use in your application.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] Validation advice is built on Bean Validation JSR 380, a specification of the Java API for bean validation which ensures that the properties of a bean meet specific criteria, using `jakarta.validation` annotations such as `@NotNull`, `@Min`, and `@Max`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] See the section on Bean Validation for more information on how to apply validation rules to your bean classes.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] Like Spring and Grails, the Micronaut framework provides caching annotations in the io.micronaut.cache package.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] The CacheManager interface allows different cache implementations to be plugged in as necessary.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] The SyncCache interface provides a synchronous API for caching, whilst the AsyncCache API allows non-blocking operation.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] Using one of these annotations activates the CacheInterceptor, which in the case of `@Cacheable` caches the return value of the method.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] The emitted result is cached if the method return type is a non-blocking type (either CompletableFuture or an instance of Publisher) .
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] In addition, if the underlying Cache implementation supports non-blocking cache operations, cache values are read without blocking, resulting in non-blocking cache operations.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] By default, Caffeine is used to create caches from application configuration.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] The above example configures a cache called "my-cache" with a maximum size of 20.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] To configure a weigher to be used with the `maximumWeight` configuration, create a bean that implements `io.micronaut.caffeine.cache.Weigher`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] To associate a given weigher with only a specific cache, annotate the bean with `@Named(<cache name>)`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] Weighers without a named qualifier apply to all caches that don’t have a named weigher.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] If no beans are found, a default implementation is used.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] See the configuration reference for all available configuration options.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] A DynamicCacheManager bean can be registered for use cases where caches cannot be configured ahead of time.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] When a cache is attempted to be retrieved that was not predefined, the dynamic cache manager is invoked to create and return a cache.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] By default, if there is no other dynamic cache manager defined in the application, the Micronaut framework registers an instance of DefaultDynamicCacheManager that creates Caffeine caches with default values.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] Check the Micronaut Cache project for more information.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] In distributed systems and microservice environments, failure is something you have to plan for, and it is common to want to attempt to retry an operation if it fails.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] With this in mind, the Micronaut framework includes a Retryable annotation.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] The simplest form of retry is just to add the `@Retryable` annotation to a type or method.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] The default behaviour of `@Retryable` is to retry three times with a linear delay of one second between each retry.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] (first attempt with 1s delay, second attempt with 2s delay, third attempt with 3s delay).
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] With the above example if the `listBooks()` method throws an Exception, it is retried until the maximum number of attempts is reached.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] The `multiplier` value of the `@Retryable` annotation can be used to configure a multiplier used to calculate the delay between retries, allowing exponential retry support.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] Notice how both `attempts` and `delay` are defined as strings.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] This is to support configurability through annotation metadata.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] With the above in place, if `book.retry.attempts` is specified in configuration it is bound to the value of the `attempts` member of the `@Retryable` annotation via annotation metadata.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] `@Retryable` advice can also be applied to methods that return reactive types, such as `Publisher` (Project Reactor's `Flux` or RxJava's `Flowable`).
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] In this case `@Retryable` advice applies the retry policy to the reactive type.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] Retry is useful in a microservice environment, but in some cases excessive retries can overwhelm the system as clients repeatedly re-attempt failing operations.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] The Circuit Breaker pattern is designed to resolve this issue by allowing a certain number of failing requests and then opening a circuit that remains open for a period before allowing additional retry attempts.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] The CircuitBreaker annotation is a variation of the `@Retryable` annotation that supports a `reset` member which indicates how long the circuit should remain open before it is reset (the default is 20 seconds).
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] The above example retries the `findBooks` method three times and then opens the circuit for 30 seconds, rethrowing the original exception and preventing potential downstream traffic such as HTTP requests and I/O operations flooding the system.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] For cases where annotations are not desirable, Micronaut Retry also provides programmatic retry creation through typed policies and injected factory beans.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] The programmatic API uses typed values such as `Duration` and `int` instead of annotation strings.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] Programmatic circuit breakers are created in the same way, using a typed `CircuitBreakerPolicy` and an injected `CircuitBreakerOperationsFactory`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] The resulting `CircuitBreakerOperations` instance owns the shared breaker state.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] When @Retryable is applied to bean factory methods, it behaves as if the annotation was placed on the type being returned.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] The retry behavior applies when the methods on the returned object are invoked.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] Note that the bean factory method itself is **not** retried.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] If you want the functionality of creating the bean to be retried, it should be delegated to another singleton that has the @Retryable annotation applied.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] You can register RetryEventListener instances as beans to listen for RetryEvent events that are published every time an operation is retried.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] In addition, you can register event listeners for CircuitOpenEvent to be notified when a circuit breaker circuit is opened, or CircuitClosedEvent for when a circuit is closed.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] Like Spring and Grails, the Micronaut framework features a Scheduled annotation for scheduling background tasks.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] The Scheduled annotation can be added to any method of a bean, and you should set one of the `fixedRate`, `fixedDelay`, or `cron` members.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] To schedule a task at a fixed rate, use the `fixedRate` member.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] The task above executes every five minutes.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] To schedule a task, so it runs five minutes after the termination of the previous task use the `fixedDelay` member.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] The above example runs the task every Monday morning at 10:15AM in the time zone of the server.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] The above example only runs once, one minute after the server starts.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] To make your application’s tasks configurable, you can use annotation metadata and property placeholder configuration.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] The above example allows the task execution frequency to be configured with the property `my.task.rate`, and the initial delay to be configured with the property `my.task.delay`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] Tasks executed by `@Scheduled` are run by default on a ScheduledExecutorService configured to have twice the number of threads as available processors.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] By default, the Micronaut framework includes a DefaultTaskExceptionHandler bean that implements the TaskExceptionHandler interface and simply logs the exception if an error occurs invoking a scheduled task.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] If you have custom requirements you can replace this bean with your own implementation (for example to send an email or shutdown the context to fail fast).
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] To do so, write your own TaskExceptionHandler and annotate it with `@Replaces(DefaultTaskExceptionHandler.class)`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] Although the Micronaut framework’s design is based on a compile-time approach and does not rely on Spring dependency injection, there is still a lot of value in the Spring ecosystem that does not depend directly on the Spring container.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] You may wish to use existing Spring projects within the Micronaut framework and configure beans to be used within the Micronaut framework.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] You may also wish to leverage existing AOP advice from Spring.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] One example of this is Spring’s support for declarative transactions with `@Transactional`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] The Micronaut framework provides support for Spring-based transaction management without requiring Spring itself.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] This is done by intercepting method calls annotated with Spring’s `@Transactional` with TransactionInterceptor.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] The benefit here is you can use Micronaut’s compile-time, reflection-free AOP to declare programmatic Spring transactions.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] Micronaut framework includes both non-blocking HTTP server and client APIs based on Netty.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] The goal of the HTTP server is to make it as easy as possible to expose services to be consumed by HTTP clients and web pages, regardless of the language they are written in.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] There is support for rendering HTML from a variety of templating frameworks in the Micronaut Views module.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] By default, the server runs on port 8080.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] The @Controller annotation used in the previous section is one of several annotations that allow you to control the construction of HTTP routes.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] The value of the `@Controller` annotation is an RFC-6570 URI template, so you can embed URI variables within the path using the syntax defined by the URI template specification.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] The actual implementation is handled by the UriMatchTemplate class, which extends UriTemplate.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p09] You can use UriTemplate to build paths to include in your responses.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p10] URI variables can be referenced via method arguments.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p10] When the path variable matches the method argument name, they are bound together automatically.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p10] If you want to use different names or specify a default value for a missing URI Variable, the PathVariable annotation can be used.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p10] The Micronaut framework maps the URI `/issues/{number}` for the above controller.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p10] Note that the URI template in the previous example requires that the `number` variable is specified.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p10] You can specify optional URI templates with the syntax: `/issues{/number}` and by annotating the `number` parameter with `@Nullable`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p10] Alternatively, you can use the `defaultValue` element of the PathVariable annotation to specify a default value when the URI variable is missing.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p10] By default, URI variables as defined by the RFC-6570 URI template spec cannot include reserved characters such as `/`, `?` etc.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p10] This can be problematic if you wish to match or expand entire paths.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p10] As per section 3.2.3 of the specification, you can use reserved expansion or matching using the `+` operator.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p10] For example the URI `/books/{+path}` matches both `/books/foo` and `/books/foo/bar` since the `+` indicates that the variable `path` should include reserved characters (in this case `/`).
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p10] The previous example uses the @Get annotation to add a method that accepts HTTP GET requests.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p10] The RouteCondition annotation allows you to define a condition that must evaluate to `true` for a route to match a request.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p10] The condition is specified as a Micronaut Expression Language (EL) expression and is evaluated at request time.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p10] Within the expression, a `request` variable is available that references the current HttpRequest.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p10] This is useful for routing requests based on query parameters, headers, or any other aspect of the request.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p10] CORS support handles OPTIONS preflight requests.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p10] Each of the routing annotations supports multiple URI templates.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p10] This feature is useful for example to change the path of the API and leave the existing path as is for backwards compatibility.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p10] If you prefer to not use annotations and instead declare all routes in code then never fear, the Micronaut framework has a flexible RouteBuilder API that makes it a breeze to define routes programmatically.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p10] The Micronaut framework supports validating route arguments at compile time with the validation library.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p10] With the correct dependency on your classpath, route arguments will automatically be checked at compile time.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p10] An optional variable is one that allows the route to match a URI even if the value is not present.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p10] For example `/foo{/bar}` matches requests to `/foo` and `/foo/abc`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p10] The non-optional variant would be `/foo/{bar}`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p10] See the URI Path Variables section for more information.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p10] The `@CustomHttpMethod` annotation supports non-standard HTTP methods for a client or server.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p10] Specifications like RFC-4918 Webdav require additional methods like REPORT or LOCK for example.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p10] The annotation can be used anywhere the standard method annotations can be used, including controllers and declarative HTTP clients.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p10] The RouteMatch API provides information about an executable Route.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p10] The examples in the previous section demonstrate how the Micronaut framework lets you bind method parameters from URI path variables.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p10] This section shows how to bind arguments from other parts of the request.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p10] All binding annotations support customization of the name of the variable being bound from with their `name` member.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p10] The method parameter name is used when a value is not specified in a binding annotation.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p10] Because hyphens are not allowed in variable names, it may be necessary to set the name in the annotation.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p10] The Micronaut framework also supports binding the body to an `InputStream`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p10] If the method is reading the stream, the method execution must be offloaded to another thread pool to avoid blocking the event loop.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p10] Instead of binding from a single section of the request, it may be desirable to bind all query values for example to a POJO.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p10] This can be achieved by using the exploded operator (`?pojo*`) in the URI template.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p10] Instead of binding just query values, it is also possible to bind any Bindable value to a POJO (e.g. to bind `HttpRequest`, `@PathVariable`, `@QueryValue` and `@Header` to a single POJO).
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p10] This can be achieved with the `@RequestBean` annotation and a custom Bean class with fields with Bindable annotations, or fields that can be bound by type (e.g.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p10] `HttpRequest`, `BasicAuth`, `Authentication`, etc).
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p10] The bean class has to be introspected with `@Introspected`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p10] Immutable Bean class with getters and an all-argument constructor (or `@Creator` annotation on a constructor or static method).
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p10] Arguments of the constructor must match field names so the object can be instantiated without reflection.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p10] Generally any type that can be converted from a String representation to a Java type via the ConversionService API can be bound to.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p10] However, you can simply add additional TypeConverter either by defining it as a bean or by registering it in a TypeConverterRegistrar via the service loader.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p10] The handling of nullability deserves special mention.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p10] In this case, if the HTTP header `Content-Type` is not present in the request, the route is considered invalid, since it cannot be satisfied, and an HTTP 400 `BAD REQUEST` is returned.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p10] A `null` string is passed if the header is absent from the request.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p10] Additionally, any `DateTime` that conforms to RFC-1123 can be bound to a parameter.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p10] Some parameters are recognized by their type instead of their annotation.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p10] From query parameters if the request is a `GET` request (e.g.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p10] If there is a `@Body` and request allows the body, bind the body to it.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p10] If the request can have a body and no `@Body` is defined then try to parse the body (either JSON or form data) and bind the method arguments from the body (see the example).
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p10] Finally, if the method arguments cannot be populated return `400 BAD REQUEST`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p11] The Micronaut framework uses an ArgumentBinderRegistry to look up ArgumentBinder beans capable of binding to the arguments in controller methods.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p11] The default implementation looks for an annotation on the argument that is meta-annotated with @Bindable.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p11] If one exists the argument binder registry searches for an argument binder that supports that annotation.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p11] If no fitting annotation is found, the Micronaut framework tries to find an argument binder that supports the argument type.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p11] An argument binder returns a ArgumentBinder.BindingResult.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p11] The binding result gives the Micronaut framework more information than just the value.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p11] Binding results are either satisfied or unsatisfied, and either empty or not empty.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p11] If an argument binder returns an unsatisfied result, the binder may be called again at different times in request processing.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p11] Argument binders are initially called before the body is read and before any filters are executed.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p11] If a binder relies on any of that data, and it is not present, return a ArgumentBinder.BindingResult#UNSATISFIED result.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p11] Returning an ArgumentBinder.BindingResult#EMPTY or satisfied result will be the final result and the binder will not be called again for that request.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p11] Argument binders that bind based on the presence of an annotation must implement AnnotatedRequestArgumentBinder, and can be used by creating an annotation that is annotated with Bindable.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p11] Once the binder is created, we can annotate an argument in our controller method which will be bound using the custom logic we’ve specified.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p11] Argument binders that bind based on the type of the argument must implement TypedRequestArgumentBinder.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p11] You may need to resolve the host name of the current server.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p11] The Micronaut framework includes an implementation of the HttpHostResolver interface.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p11] If the `X-Forwarded-Host` header is not present, the other `X-Forwarded` headers are ignored.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p11] The above configuration also supports an allowed host list.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p11] Configuring this list ensures any resolved host matches one of the supplied regular expression patterns.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p11] That is useful to prevent host cache poisoning attacks and is recommended to be configured.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p11] The Micronaut framework supports several strategies for resolving locales for a given request.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p11] The getLocale-- method is available on the request, however it only supports parsing the `Accept-Language` header.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p11] For other use cases where the locale can be in a cookie, the user’s session, or should be set to a fixed value, HttpLocaleResolver can be used to determine the current locale.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p11] The LocaleResolver API does not need to be used directly.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p11] Simply define a parameter to a controller method of type `java.util.Locale` and the locale will be resolved and injected automatically.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p11] Locales can be configured in the "en_GB" format, or in the BCP 47 (Language tag) format.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p11] If multiple methods are configured, the fixed locale takes precedence, followed by session/cookie, then header.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p11] If any of the built-in methods do not meet your use case, create a bean of type HttpLocaleResolver and set its order (through the `getOrder` method) relative to the existing resolvers.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p11] You may need to resolve the originating IP address of an HTTP Request.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p11] The Micronaut framework includes an implementation of HttpClientAddressResolver.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p11] The first priority header name can be configured with `micronaut.server.client-address-header`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p11] If you need more control over request processing you can write a method that receives the complete HttpRequest.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p11] In fact, there are several higher-level interfaces that can be bound to controller method parameters.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p11] In addition, for full control over the emitted HTTP response you can use the static factory methods of the HttpResponse class which return a MutableHttpResponse.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p11] The HttpRequest is also available from a static context via ServerRequestContext.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p11] An alternative for users of Project Reactor to using the ServerRequestContext is to use the contextual features of Project Reactor to retrieve the request.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p11] Because the Micronaut Framework uses Project Reactor as it’s default reactive streams implementation, users of Project Reactor can benefit by being able to access the request in the context.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p11] Using the context to retrieve the request is the best approach for reactive flows because Project Reactor propagates the context, and it does not rely on a thread local like ServerRequestContext.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p11] A Micronaut controller action responds with a 200 HTTP status code by default.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p11] If the action returns an `HttpResponse`, configure the status code for the response with the `status` method.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p11] You can also use the `@Status` annotation.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p11] Micronaut supports arbitrary HTTP status codes not part of the predefined `HttpStatus` enum.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p11] A Micronaut controller action produces `application/json` by default.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p11] However, you can change the `Content-Type` of the response with the `@Produces` annotation or the `produces` member of the HTTP method annotations.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p11] A Micronaut controller action consumes `application/json` by default.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p11] Consuming other content types is supported with the `@Consumes` annotation, or the `consumes` member of any HTTP method annotation.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p11] Normally JSON parsing only happens if the content type is `application/json`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p11] The other MediaTypeCodec classes behave similarly in that they have predefined content types they can process.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p11] The currently supported configuration prefixes are `json`, `json-stream`, `text`, and `text-stream`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p11] As mentioned previously, Micronaut framework is built on Netty which is designed around an Event loop model and non-blocking I/O.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p11] Micronaut executes code defined in @Controller beans in the same thread as the request thread (an Event Loop thread).
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p11] This makes it critical that if you do any blocking I/O operations (for example interactions with Hibernate/JPA or JDBC) that you offload those tasks to a separate thread pool that does not block the Event loop.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p11] To use this thread pool in a @Controller bean you have a number of options.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p11] The simplest is to use the @ExecuteOn annotation, which can be applied only to either a @Controller or @Filter at the type or method level.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p11] The value of the @ExecuteOn annotation can be any named executor defined under `micronaut.executors`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p11] An alternative to the @ExecuteOn annotation is to use the facility provided by the reactive library you have chosen.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p11] Reactive implementations such as Project Reactor or RxJava feature a `subscribeOn` method which lets you alter which thread executes user code.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p12] To parse the request body, you first indicate to the Micronaut framework which parameter receives the data with the Body annotation.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p12] Note that reading the request body is done in a non-blocking manner in that the request contents are read as the data becomes available and accumulated into the String passed to the method.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p12] Regardless of the limit, for a large amount of data accumulating the data into a String in-memory may lead to memory strain on the server.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p12] The previous section introduced the notion of Reactive programming using Project Reactor and Micronaut.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p12] The Micronaut framework supports returning common reactive types such as Mono (or Single Maybe Observable types from RxJava), an instance of Publisher or CompletableFuture from any controller method.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p12] The argument designated as the body of the request using the Body annotation can also be a reactive type or a CompletableFuture.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p12] When returning a reactive type, The Micronaut framework subscribes to the returned reactive type on the same thread as the request (a Netty Event Loop thread).
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p12] It is therefore important that if you perform any blocking operations, you offload those operations to an appropriately configured thread pool, for example using the Project Reactor or RxJava `subscribeOn(..)` facility or @ExecuteOn.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p12] The most common data interchange format nowadays is JSON.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p12] By default, the Controller annotation specifies that the controllers in Micronaut framework consume and produce JSON by default.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p12] Since Micronaut Framework 4.0, users must choose how they want to serialize (Jackson Databind or Micronaut Serialization).
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p12] Both approaches allow the usage of Jackson Annotations.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p12] With either approach, the Micronaut framework reads incoming JSON in a non-blocking manner.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p12] Micronaut Serialization offers reflection-free serialization using build-time Bean Introspections.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p12] It supports alternative formats such as JSON-P or JSON-B.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p12] You may be familiar with Jackson’s `ObjectMapper`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p12] For implementation-agnostic application code, we recommend depending on JsonMapper, which is Micronaut’s JSON abstraction for common mapping operations.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p12] Micronaut Serialization and Micronaut Jackson Databind both provide implementations of JsonMapper, and Micronaut Serialization also defines its own `ObjectMapper` interface that extends JsonMapper.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p12] If you are intentionally writing implementation-specific code, you can still use the corresponding implementation API such as Jackson’s `ObjectMapper` or Micronaut Serialization’s `ObjectMapper`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p12] You can inject a bean of type `JsonMapper` or manually instantiate one via `JsonMapper.createDefault()`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p12] From a developer perspective however, you can generally just work with Plain Old Java Objects (POJOs) and can optionally use a Reactive framework such as RxJava or Project Reactor.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p12] The above example uses the `thenApply` method to achieve the same as the previous example.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p12] The Micronaut framework only executes your method once the data has been read in a non-blocking manner.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p12] If you use `micronaut-jackson-databind`, the Jackson `ObjectMapper` can be configured through configuration with the JacksonConfiguration class.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p12] This section is specific to the Jackson implementation; for application code that should remain portable across Micronaut JSON implementations, prefer depending on JsonMapper.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p12] All Jackson configuration keys start with `jackson`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p12] If you use `micronaut-jackson-databind`, all Jackson’s features can be configured with their name as the key and a boolean to indicate enabled or disabled.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p12] Please check the configuration reference for the property names.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p12] If you use `micronaut-jackson-databind`, there may be situations where you wish to customise the `JsonFactory` used by the `ObjectMapper` beyond the configuration of features (for example to allow custom character escaping).
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p12] This can be achieved by providing your own `JsonFactory` bean, or by providing a `BeanCreatedEventListener<JsonFactory>` which configures the default bean on startup.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p12] If you use `micronaut-jackson-databind`, you can use the `@JsonView` annotation on controller methods if you set `jackson.json-view.enabled` to `true` in your configuration file (e.g `application.yml`).
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p12] Jackson’s `@JsonView` annotation lets you control which properties are exposed on a per-response basis.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p12] See Jackson JSON Views for more information.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p12] If you use `micronaut-jackson-databind`, in addition to configuration, beans can be registered to customize Jackson.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p12] Any modules registered via the service loader are also added to the default object mapper.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p12] During JSON parsing, the framework may convert any incoming data to an intermediate object model.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p12] By default, this model uses `BigInteger`, `long` and `double` for numeric values.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p12] This means some information that could be represented by `BigDecimal` may be lost.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p12] For example, numbers with many decimal places that cannot be represented by `double` may be truncated, even if the target type for deserialization uses `BigDecimal`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p12] Metadata on the number of trailing zeroes (`BigDecimal.precision()`), e.g. the difference between `0.12` and `0.120`, is also discarded.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p12] By default, a Micronaut Controller responds with content-type `application/json`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p12] However, you can respond with content type `text/plain` by annotating the controller method with the @Produces annotation.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p12] It is easy to validate incoming data with Micronaut controllers using Validation Advice.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p12] We can validate parameters using `jakarta.validation` annotations and the Validated annotation at the class level.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p12] If a validation error occurs a `jakarta.validation.ConstraintViolationException` is thrown.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p12] Often you may want to use POJOs as controller method parameters.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p12] Annotate your controller with Validated, and annotate the binding POJO with `@Valid`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p12] You can enforce a subset of constraints using validation groups using `groups` on Validated.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p12] Annotate your controller with Validated, specifying the validation groups that will be active or letting it default to `Default`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p12] Also annotate the binding POJO with `@Valid`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p12] Static resource resolution is enabled by default.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p12] The Micronaut framework supports resolving resources from the classpath or the file system.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p12] Sometimes with distributed applications, bad things happen.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p12] Having a good way to handle errors is important.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p12] The @Error annotation supports defining either an exception class or an HTTP status.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p12] Methods annotated with @Error must be defined within a class annotated with @Controller.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p12] The annotation also supports the notion of global and local, local being the default.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p12] Local error handlers only respond to exceptions thrown as a result of the route being matched to another method in the same controller.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p12] Global error handlers can be invoked as a result of any thrown exception.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p12] A local error handler is always searched for first when resolving which handler to execute.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p12] Similar to other controller methods, error handlers can use request binding annotations on parameters e.g. to access header values.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p12] However, binding the request body comes with additional restrictions depending on the HTTP server implementation used.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p12] If the body has already been bound to a parameter of the original controller method, it may not be possible to bind the body to a different type, as the original bytes may already have been discarded.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p13] Alternatively, you can implement an ExceptionHandler, a generic hook for handling exceptions that occur during execution of an HTTP request.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p13] The server returns a 500 (Internal Server Error) status code if you don’t handle the exception.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p13] The Micronaut framework produces error responses via a bean of type ErrorResponseProcessor.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p13] JSON error responses are provided with a bean of type JsonErrorResponseBodyProvider.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p13] The default implementation outputs vnd.error responses.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p13] HTML error responses are provided via a bean of type HtmlErrorResponseBodyProvider.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p13] The default implementation outputs HTML which can be localized with codes such as: `<status>.error.bold`, `<status>.error.title`, `<status>.error`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p13] If customization of the response other than items related to the errors is desired, the exception handler that is handling the exception needs to be overridden.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p13] Since 1.1.x, the Micronaut framework supports API versioning via a dedicated @Version annotation.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p13] By default, the Micronaut framework has two strategies for resolving the version based on an HTTP header named `X-API-VERSION` or a request parameter named `api-version`, however this is configurable.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p13] If this is not enough you can also implement the RequestVersionResolver interface which receives the HttpRequest and can implement any strategy you choose.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p13] It is possible to supply a default version through configuration.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p13] If the incoming request specifies a version, the default version has no effect.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p13] Micronaut’s Declarative HTTP client also supports automatic versioning of outgoing requests via the @Version annotation.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p13] By default, if you annotate a client interface with @Version, the value supplied to the annotation is included using the `X-API-VERSION` header.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p13] The `default` key refers to the default configuration.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p13] You can specify client-specific configuration by using the value passed to `@Client` (typically the service ID).
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p13] The above uses a key named `greeting-service` which can be used to configure a client annotated with `@Client('greeting-service')`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p13] To make data binding model customizations consistent between form data and JSON, the Micronaut framework uses Jackson to implement binding data from form submissions.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p13] The advantage of this approach is that the same Jackson annotations used for customizing JSON binding can be used for form submissions.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p13] As you can see from the example above, this approach lets you use features such as support for `@Nullable` or Optional types and restrict the parameters to be bound.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p13] When using POJOs you must be careful to use Jackson annotations to exclude properties that should not be bound.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p13] The Micronaut HTTP server includes support for forms, both using `multipart/form-data` and using `application/x-www-form-urlencoded` format.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p13] The lowest-level form API in the Micronaut HTTP server is the FormCapableHttpRequest.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p13] It provides a reactive Publisher of the form fields.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p13] This publisher can be subscribed to at most once.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p13] Each field is represented by a RawFormField containing the field metadata and field body as a ByteBody.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p13] The most important information in the field metadata is the field name.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p13] This corresponds to the `name` attribute on a form `input` element.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p13] File uploads contain additional metadata: The file name, and optionally, the file content type.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p13] Note that there is no restriction on this metadata.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p13] Multiple fields may have the same name (browsers will do this when uploading multiple files), and any of the metadata fields may be missing entirely.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p13] The field body is represented by a ByteBody, which is an asynchronous, streaming API.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p13] Large form fields may be processed lazily: As long as you do not consume the data from the `ByteBody`, the form data will not be read from the client, and e.g. an upload may stall.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p13] You will also not see any other fields on the main publisher, since they can only be received once all data for the current form field has arrived.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p13] For short form fields, the `ByteBody` may be fully buffered internally, but you should not rely on this.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p13] Micronaut’s HTTP server supports writing chunks of response data by returning a Publisher that emits objects that can be encoded to the HTTP response.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p13] When returning a reactive type, the server uses a `Transfer-Encoding` of `chunked` and keeps writing data until the Publisher `onComplete` method is called.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p13] The server requests a single item from the Publisher, writes it, and requests the next, controlling back pressure.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p13] In some cases you may wish to integrate a library that does not support non-blocking I/O.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p13] In this case you can return a Writable object from any controller method.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p13] The Writable interface has various signatures that allow writing to traditional blocking streams like Writer or OutputStream.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p13] When returning a Writable, the blocking I/O operation is shifted to the I/O thread pool so the Netty event loop is not blocked.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p13] Another option is to return an input stream.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p13] This is useful for many scenarios that interact with other APIs that expose a stream.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p13] Often, you want to respond 404 (Not Found) when you don’t find an item in your persistence layer or in similar scenarios.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p13] To disable 404 on a null body or an empty publisher set `micronaut.server.not-found-on-missing-body` to `false`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p13] Handling of file uploads has special treatment in Micronaut.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p13] Support is provided for streaming of uploads in a non-blocking manner through streaming uploads or completed uploads.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p13] To receive data from a multipart request, set the `consumes` argument of the method annotation to MULTIPART_FORM_DATA.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] Method argument types determine how files are received.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] Data can be received a chunk at a time or when an upload is completed.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] PartData represents a chunk of data received in a multipart request.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] PartData interface methods convert the data to a `byte[]`, InputStream, or a ByteBuffer.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] Route arguments of type Publisher are treated as intended to receive a single file, and each chunk of the received file will be sent downstream.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] If the generic type is other than PartData, conversion will be attempted using Micronaut’s conversion service.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] Conversions to `String` and `byte[]` are supported by default.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] If you need knowledge about the metadata of an uploaded file, the StreamingFileUpload class is a Publisher that also has file information such as the content type and file name.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] It is also possible to pass an output stream with the `transferTo` method.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] Route arguments that are not publishers cause route execution to be delayed until the upload has finished.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] The received data will attempt to be converted to the requested type.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] Conversions to a `String` or `byte[]` are supported by default.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] In addition, the file can be converted to a POJO if a media type codec is registered that supports the media type of the file.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] A media type codec is included by default that allows conversion of JSON files to POJOs.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] If you need knowledge about the metadata of an uploaded file, the CompletedFileUpload class has methods to retrieve the data of the file, and also file information such as the content type and file name.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] If a multipart request has multiple uploads that have different part names, create an argument to your route that receives each part.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] A route method signature like the above expects two different parts, one named "title" and the other "name".
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] To receive multiple parts with the same part name, the argument must be a Publisher.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] When used in one of the following ways, the publisher emits one item per part found with the specified name.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] When request part names aren’t known ahead of time, or to read the entire body, a special type can be used to indicate the entire body is desired.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] If a route has an argument of type MultipartBody (not to be confused with the class for the client) annotated with @Body, each part of the request will be emitted through the argument.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] A MultipartBody is a publisher of CompletedPart instances.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] The Micronaut framework supports sending files to the client in a couple of easy ways.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] It is possible to return a File object from your controller method, and the data will be returned to the client.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] The `Content-Type` header of file responses is calculated based on the name of the file.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] To control either the media type of the file being sent, or to set the file to be downloaded (i.e. using the `Content-Disposition` header), instead construct a SystemFile with the file to use.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] For cases where a reference to a `File` object is not possible (for example resources in JAR files), the Micronaut framework supports transferring input streams.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] To return a stream of data from the controller method, construct a StreamedFile.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] The server supports returning `304` (Not Modified) responses if the files being transferred have not changed, and the request contains the appropriate header.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] In addition, if the client accepts encoded responses, the Micronaut framework encodes the file if appropriate.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] Encoding happens if the file is text-based and larger than 1KB by default.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] The threshold at which data is encoded is configurable.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] See the server configuration reference for details.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] Micronaut also supports returning **reactive streams** (e.g., `Flux`, `Flowable`, or any `Publisher`) without buffering the entire response in memory.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] If you want to force the client browser to download the streamed data (for example, CSV lines), you can set the `Content-Disposition: attachment` header.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] By default, file responses include caching headers.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] The following options determine how the `Cache-Control` header is built.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] The Micronaut HTTP server supports applying filters to request/response processing in a similar (but reactive) way to Servlet filters in traditional Java applications.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] Filter patterns can be defined on the filter class (in Filter, the ServerFilter or ClientFilter annotation), or on the filter method (in the RequestFilter or ResponseFilter annotation).
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] You can use different styles of pattern for path matching by setting `patternStyle`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] By default, AntPathMatcher is used for path matching.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] The other option is regular expression based matching.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] To use regular expressions, set `patternStyle = FilterPatternStyle.REGEX`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] The `pattern` attribute is expected to contain a regular expression which will be expected to match the provided URLs exactly (using Matcher#matches).
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] A filter method must be declared in a bean annotated with ServerFilter, or ClientFilter if it should instead intercept requests made by the HTTP client.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] Each filter method must also be annotated with RequestFilter, to run before the request is processed, or ResponseFilter, to run after the request has completed to process the response.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] A filter method can take various parameters, such as the HttpRequest and the HttpResponse (only for response filters).
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] The return type can be `void` or `null` to continue execution as normal, or an updated HttpRequest (only for request filters) or HttpResponse.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] The different supported parameter and return types are described in the documentation of RequestFilter and ResponseFilter.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] Request filters can bind the full request body using the Body annotation.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] This is useful e.g. to verify a signed request body.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] To write asynchronous filters, you can return a reactive publisher.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] To put these concepts into practice lets look at an example.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] Suppose you wish to trace each request to the "Hello World" example using some external system.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] This system could be a database or a distributed tracing service, and may require I/O operations.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] You should not block the underlying Netty event loop in your filter; instead the filter should proceed with execution once any I/O is complete.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] The previous example demonstrates some key concepts such as executing blocking logic in a worker thread before proceeding with the request and modifying the outgoing response.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] If you need to write a filter, e.g., security-related, which needs to proceed with requests in some scenarios or stop the request execution and return an HTTP Response directly in the filter; you can use, for example, a `CompletableFuture` as the filter method’s response type.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] In principle, downstream filters and controllers can produce exceptions, and response filters should be prepared to handle them.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] For a response filter to be called when there is an exception, it must declare the exception type as a parameter.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] Whether errors appear as exceptions depends on the context of the filter.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] For the Micronaut HTTP server, any exception is mapped to a non-exceptional HttpResponse with an error status code.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] This mapping happens before each filter, so a server filter will never actually see an exception.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] If you still want to access the original cause of the response, it is stored as the attribute EXCEPTION.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] Request filters can define a special FilterContinuation parameter to get more control of the downstream execution, and to be run further actions after it completes.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] Filters can be ordered by annotating the filter method or filter class with Order or jakarta.annotation.Priority, or by implementing Ordered in the filter class.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] Request filters are executed in order from the highest precedence (the smallest integer value, as defined by `Ordered.HIGHEST_PRECEDENCE`) to the lowest precedence (the biggest integer value, as defined by `Ordered.LOWEST_PRECEDENCE`).
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] Response filters are executed in reverse order.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] Micronaut applies the same numeric precedence rule to jakarta.annotation.Priority because @Priority is mapped to @Order during annotation processing.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] Request filter A is executed first, because it has the higher precedence (-100), followed by request filter B with the lower precedence (100).
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] Response filter C is executed first, because it has the lower precedence (100), and finally response filter D with the higher precedence (-100) is executed last.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] For a server application, the HttpServerFilter interface `doFilter` method can be implemented.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] The `doFilter` method accepts the HttpRequest and an instance of ServerFilterChain.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] The `ServerFilterChain` interface contains a resolved chain of filters where the final entry in the chain is the matched route.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] The ServerFilterChain.proceed(io.micronaut.http.HttpRequest) method resumes processing of the request.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] The `proceed(..)` method returns a Reactive Streams Publisher that emits the response to be returned to the client.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p14] Implementors of filters can subscribe to the Publisher and mutate the emitted MutableHttpResponse to modify the response prior to returning the response to the client.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] The following code sample shows how to implement the HttpServerFilter interface.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] The previous example demonstrates some key concepts such as executing logic in a non-blocking manner before proceeding with the request and modifying the outgoing response.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] The publisher returned from `chain.proceed` should never emit an error.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] In the cases where an upstream filter emitted an error or the route itself threw an exception, the error response should be emitted instead of the exception.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] In some cases it may be desirable to know the cause of the error response and for this purpose an attribute exists on the response if it was created as a result of an exception being emitted or thrown.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] The original cause is stored as the attribute EXCEPTION.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] Micronaut HTTP server version 4.5.0 introduced a new, more advanced API to access the bytes of an incoming request.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] When an HttpRequest implements ServerHttpRequest, the new `byteBody()` method returns a ByteBody with buffered, reactive and blocking APIs.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] When an HTTP request comes in, it starts out with an unparsed and unclaimed stream of bytes as its `byteBody()`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] After all request filters have run, typically an argument binder matching the `@Body` parameter of the controller will "claim" the `byteBody()` and e.g. parse the JSON.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] Finally, the body is closed at the end of the request lifecycle, discarding any data if it has not been claimed by the argument binder.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] `ByteBody` itself does not offer direct access to the data.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] To begin processing, there must be a *primary operation* that converts the body into another form that can be used in the application programming model.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] A normal `ByteBody` has two groups of streaming primary operations.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] `toInputStream()` gives access to the body as a regular `InputStream`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] The `toByteArrayPublisher()` and `toByteBufferPublisher()` methods return a reactive stream of byte arrays or `ByteBuffer`s.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] If you need full access to the body, the `buffer()` method returns a `CompletableFuture` that completes with an `AvailableByteBody` when the full body has been received.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] `AvailableByteBody` has a few more convenient primary operations: `toByteArray()`, `toByteBuffer()` and `toString(Charset)`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] Buffering is limited to the number of bytes configured in the `micronaut.server.max-request-buffer-size` property.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] Because the framework will not buffer the whole body in memory by default, after an ByteBody has been claimed (a primary operation has been performed), the data is "gone", and the same ByteBody cannot be claimed again.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] That means that if a filter were to claim the `ServerHttpRequest.byteBody()` directly (e.g. to print it to a log), controllers could not access it anymore.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] The argument binder for the `@Body` argument would throw an exception.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] To resolve this exclusivity problem, an `ByteBody` can be *split* before it is claimed.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] The split operation essentially duplicates the body stream so that the two consumers (logging and argument binding) can process it independently.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] A body can be `split` any number of times, but only before the primary operation.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] While `ServerHttpRequest.byteBody()` returns a normal `ByteBody` — cleanup is done by the HTTP server if the body is not consumed—the body returned by `split` is a `CloseableByteBody`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] The caller **must** ensure that the new instance is closed, otherwise there can be resource and memory leaks, stalled connections, or other issues.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] When there are two consumers of the same stream of input data, the problem of backpressure coordination necessarily comes up.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] Backpressure in an HTTP server describes the behavior when the "downstream" consumers cannot consume data as fast as the "upstream" supplier (i.e. the HTTP client sending the request) is sending it.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] To avoid having to buffer large amounts of incoming data, the server will apply backpressure (make the client send its data more slowly) when downstream consumers cannot keep up.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] A `split` operation now introduces two consumers.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] Depending on use case, different approaches of dealing with the backpressure of each downstream consumer may be appropriate.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] For example, if the two consumers write the body data to two separate files at the same time, it’s best to use the backpressure of the slowest consumer to avoid buffering data.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] But in another example, when one consumer is a filter that needs access to all the body data, and the other consumer is the controller, the filter needs to complete before the controller even reads any data, so we should instead be guided by the fastest of the two consumers.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] These two approaches are already the two most important SplitBackpressureModes.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] The argument-less `split()` method uses `SLOWEST`, but you should pick the mode that is most appropriate for your use case.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] Some consumers end up not needing the body after all.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] For example, if a `POST` request cannot be matched to a controller route, the body is not needed and can be discarded.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] How discarding is implemented in the server depends on HTTP version.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] For HTTP/1, the server might close the connection or simply drop the data (which can still save some decompression overhead).
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] For HTTP/2 the server can close the input of the request stream, instructing the client to send no more data.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] When there are multiple consumers, discard behavior is dependent on use case.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] In the above scenario of an unmatched request, when there is a filter that is also subscribed to the body data, it may be appropriate to drop the request in some cases (e.g. for logging) but may be necessary to still receive all the data in others.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] To signal that the upstream may discard the body, you can call `ByteBody.allowDiscard()`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] Only if all consumers call `allowDiscard()` (or `close()` without a primary operation) may the remaining data actually be discarded.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] Before that, *all* consumers, even those that called `allowDiscard()`, will still receive all data.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] For the logging use case, you can call `allowDiscard()` and be assured that you will still log the full body if the controller needs it.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] This example adds a filter that will log the body bytes as they come in.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] With a short body like this, the log will only show one "packet".
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] Note that the logging in the above example is asynchronous, so the log statements may be interleaved as shown.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] See the documentation for Micronaut Session for information about supporting HTTP sessions in your applications.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] The Micronaut HTTP server supports emitting Server Sent Events (SSE) using the Event API.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] To emit events from the server, return a Reactive Streams Publisher that emits objects of type Event.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] The Publisher itself could publish events from a background task, via an event system, etc.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] To emit news headline events, write a controller that returns a Publisher of Event instances using whichever Reactive library you prefer.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] You can use the methods of the Event interface to customize the Server Sent Event data sent back, including associating event ids, comments, retry timeouts, etc.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] The Micronaut framework features dedicated support for creating WebSocket clients and servers.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] The io.micronaut.websocket.annotation package includes annotations for defining both clients and servers.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] The @ServerWebSocket annotation can be applied to any class that should map to a WebSocket URI.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] The @OnClose method can optionally receive a CloseReason.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] The `@OnClose` method is invoked prior to the session closing.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] The @OnMessage method can define a parameter for the message body.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] A method annotated with @OnError can be added to implement custom error handling.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] The `@OnError` method can define a parameter that receives the exception type to be handled.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] If no `@OnError` handling is present and an unrecoverable exception occurs, the WebSocket is automatically closed.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] The callback methods of a @ServerWebSocket are invoked on the main Netty server event loop by default.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] If you do any blocking I/O operations in your WebSocket handler methods, then you must offload those tasks to a separate thread pool in the same manner as with HTTP.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] As with a @Controller or @Filter, the @ExecuteOn annotation can be applied to a @ServerWebSocket handler at either the type or method level.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] The previous example uses the `broadcastSync` method of the WebSocketBroadcaster interface which blocks until the broadcast is complete.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] A similar `sendSync` method exists in WebSocketSession to send a message to a single receiver in a blocking manner.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] You can however implement non-blocking WebSocket servers by instead returning a Publisher or a Future from each WebSocket handler method.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] The example above uses `broadcast`, which creates an instance of Publisher and returns the value to Micronaut.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] The Micronaut framework sends the message asynchronously based on the Publisher interface.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] The similar `send` method sends a single message asynchronously via Micronaut return value.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] For sending messages asynchronously outside Micronaut annotated handler methods, you can use `broadcastAsync` and `sendAsync` methods in their respective WebSocketBroadcaster and WebSocketSession interfaces.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] For blocking sends, the `broadcastSync` and `sendSync` methods can be used.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] By default, the `@ServerWebSocket` instance is shared for all WebSocket connections.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] Extra care must be taken to synchronize local state to avoid thread safety issues.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] If you prefer to have an instance for each connection, annotate the class with @Prototype.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] This lets you retrieve the WebSocketSession from the `@OnOpen` handler and assign it to a field of the `@ServerWebSocket` instance.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] The WebSocketSession is by default backed by an in-memory map.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] If you add the `session` module you can however share sessions between the HTTP server and the WebSocket server.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] By default, Micronaut framework times out idle connections with no activity after five minutes.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] The @ClientWebSocket annotation can be used with the WebSocketClient interface to define WebSocket clients.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] This lets you use the same service discovery and load balancing features for WebSocket clients.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] Once you have a reference to the WebSocketClient interface you can use the `connect` method to obtain a connected instance of a bean annotated with @ClientWebSocket.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] You can also define abstract methods that start with either `send` or `broadcast` and these methods will be implemented for you at compile time.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] Note by returning `void` this tells the Micronaut framework that the method is a blocking send.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] The above example defines a send method that returns a Mono.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p15] The above example defines a send method that executes asynchronously and returns a Future to access the results.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p16] Since Micronaut framework 2.x, Micronaut Netty-based HTTP server can be configured to support HTTP/2.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p16] With this configuration, the Micronaut framework enables support for the `h2c` protocol (see HTTP/2 over cleartext) which is fine for development.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p16] Since browsers don’t support `h2c` and in general HTTP/2 over TLS (the `h2` protocol), it is recommended for production that you enable HTTPS support.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p16] For production, see the configuring HTTPS section of the documentation.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p16] In addition to a dependency on the appropriate native library for your architecture.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p16] See the documentation on Tomcat Native for more information.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p16] Support for server push has been added in Micronaut framework 3.2.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p16] Server push allows for a single request to trigger multiple responses.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p16] This is most often used in the case of browser based resources.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p16] The goal is to improve latency for the client, because they do not have to request that resource manually anymore, and can save a round trip.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p16] A new interface, PushCapableHttpRequest, has been created to support the feature.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p16] Simply add a PushCapableHttpRequest parameter to a controller method and use its API to trigger additional requests.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p16] Before triggering additional requests, the `isServerPushSupported()` method should be called to ensure the feature is available.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p16] Once it’s known the feature is supported, use the `serverPush(HttpRequest)` method to trigger additional requests.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p16] For example: `request.serverPush(HttpRequest.GET("/static/style.css"))`).
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p16] Since Micronaut framework 4.x, Micronaut’s Netty-based HTTP server can be configured to support HTTP/3.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p16] Instead of the TCP used for HTTP/1.1 and HTTP/2, HTTP/3 runs on UDP.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p16] The HTTP server emits a number of Bean Events, defined in the io.micronaut.runtime.server.event package, that you can write listeners for.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p16] The HTTP server features a number of configuration options.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p16] They are defined in the NettyHttpServerConfiguration configuration class, which extends HttpServerConfiguration.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p16] The native Netty transports add features specific to a particular platform, generate less garbage, and generally improve performance when compared to the NIO-based transport.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p16] The first available transport out of those listed will be used.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p16] If you want to make sure native transports will be used in all environments, remove the `nio` entry.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p16] An exception will be thrown if no native transport is available.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p16] The HTTP server is built on Netty which is designed as a non-blocking I/O toolkit in an event loop model.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p16] The Netty worker event loop uses the "default" named event loop group.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p16] This can be configured through `micronaut.netty.event-loops.default`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p16] When dealing with blocking operations, the Micronaut framework shifts the blocking operations to an unbound, caching I/O thread pool by default.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p16] You can configure the I/O thread pool using the ExecutorConfiguration named `io`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p16] The above configuration creates a fixed thread pool with 75 threads.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p16] Since Java 19, the JVM includes experimental support for virtual threads ("project loom").
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p16] As it is a preview feature, you need to pass `--enable-preview` as a JVM parameter to enable it.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p16] The Micronaut framework will detect virtual thread support and use it for the executor named `blocking` if available.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p16] If virtual threads are not supported, this executor will be aliased to the `io` thread pool.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p16] Micronaut HTTP Server Netty 4.9 introduces an **experimental** mode to run virtual threads on the Netty event loop.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p16] This can improve performance of virtual threads, since it avoids a context switch between the Netty event loop and the JDK ForkJoinPool.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p16] This mode requires access to internal JDK APIs.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p16] Please run your application with `--add-opens=java.base/java.lang=ALL-UNNAMED`.
[src:micronaut/guide-index-p16] Then, enable the `loom-carrier` flag for the event loop, e.g.
